<HEADLINE> Can Americans Adjust Downward?  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CUNNIFF
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Americans adjust their finances upward much
better than downward. They know how to spend during good times, but
that very tendency causes them hardship when times get tough.
</P>
<P>
   It now tests their ability to withstand higher interest rates,
and all that higher interest rates could mean, such as layoffs,
costlier credit cards, falling stocks and rising mortgage rates.
</P>
<P>
   It could also test the image of middle Americans living the good
life, as portrayed in leisure and travel magazines and indicated
statistically by the record percentage of homeowners (68 percent),
and the late-model cars in the driveway (almost 17 million sold
last year).
</P>
<P>
   The question to be answered is how durable are the good times,
and how much they are merely the benefits of low unemployment, easy
credit, rising stocks, unrealistically high expectations, and just
plain good luck.
</P>
<P>
   The question coincides with publication of ''The Fragile Middle
Class'' (Yale University Press) by three professors who view
prosperity as not quite so durable as depicted, mainly because of
debts. Some of our miracle families -- those with ''everything'' --
they say, ''only appear to be afloat.''
</P>
<P>
   They picture thousands of families hauling so heavy a financial
load over thin ice that they could go crashing through. The
precipitators: income interruptions, credit cards and other
consumer debt, accidents and illnesses, divorce, home mortgages.
They refer to ''drowning-by-mortgage.''
</P>
<P>
   The authors, Teresa Sullivan and Jay Lawrence Westbrook of the
University of Texas, and Elizabeth Warren of Harvard, observe that
amid prosperity there is a line of clouds. It could, they say, be
''just another summer squall or a terrible storm headed our way.''
</P>
<P>
   While they didn't necessarily have the Federal Reserve in mind
when they wrote their book, their comments indicate the sensitivity
of the Fed's pursuit of an economic slowdown by raising interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Rising interest rates, for example, are generally considered
deadly for stocks, which represented almost a third of household
wealth, a total of $13.3 trillion at the end of 1999, a 20
percent-plus gain in one year.
</P>
<P>
   A decline in such assets could deflate the so-called wealth
effect and, in the case of stocks bought with borrowed money,
create financial hardships. In either case, the impact would be
felt in lower sales, profits and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The impact could be equally bad or worse at the lower end of the
financial scale, mainly among those with few skills and only a
tenuous hold on employment. This group would include former welfare
recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Should these people be badly affected, it would represent a sad
irony of the economic boom. For years, the lowest 20 percent of the
income scale suffered from minimal gains, but in the latest
five-year period their percentage improvements have exceeded those
of the sectors above them.
</P>
<P>
   While any slowdown of the expansion will mostly be felt in the
pocketbook, its effects may reverberate into the social and
political areas as well. It could, for example, worsen the wealth
gap between whites and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   These are but some of the sensitivities that could be exposed by
continued interest rate increases. While the six increases since
June have had little impact, it has only made the Fed more
hard-nosed.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the big test -- for the Fed, for stocks, for borrowers,
for political leadership, for rich and poor. It's the big test.
After such good times, can the fragile household adjust downward
smoothly?
</P>
<P>
   
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-18-00 0015 </TRAILER>
