<HEADLINE> Cramer Threatens To Ax Fox Show  </HEADLINE>
By SETH SUTEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- TheStreet.com is threatening to pull its
television show off the Fox News Channel, claiming the cable
network disparaged Jim Cramer, the Web site's co-founder and most
visible commentator.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox said Wednesday the Web company is still under contract
for another year and fully expects the show to continue. The show,
called ''TheStreet.com,'' airs on Saturday mornings.
</P>
<P>
   It was the latest exchange of blows in a dispute that began in
mid-April when Cramer, in one of his regular appearances,
recommended buying shares of TheStreet.com, in which he owns a 13
percent stake. The shares were trading at around $6 at the time,
well below their high of $48.75 reached last May.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Clarke, CEO of the Web site, said TheStreet.com was
canceling the show because the company was disappointed with Fox's
efforts to expand the reach of the show, and because Fox had
disparaged the company publicly and breached a contract with it.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke was referring to an article in the New York Daily News on
April 26 in which a Fox official was quoted as saying ''we do not
approve of the touting of stock for personal gain on the air.''
Clarke said TheStreet.com interpreted that remark to be a new
policy imposed by Fox regarding on-air disclosures.
</P>
<P>
   Dianne Brandi, vice president for legal affairs at Fox News,
said Cramer remains under contract to do the show for another year.
She dismissed arguments that Fox breached its contract with
TheStreet.com or tarnished the company's image.
</P>
<P>
   ''The simple truth is that Mr. Cramer touted TheStreet.com stock
in an inappropriate manner on the television program,'' Brandi
said. ''TheStreet.com has made unfounded assertions and has put
forth the unfathomable claim that a published newspaper article
permits Mr. Cramer and TheStreet.com to walk away from his and its
obligations.''
</P>
<P>
   Cramer's remarks on the show had also drawn a rebuke from the
top editor at TheStreet.com. Dave Kansas, in a column published
April 15, wrote: ''I don't like Cramer or anyone else discussing
our stock on the show or on the site. You have to take his view on
this with your own heavy grain of salt.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Cramer has found himself in hot water
over statements he made on the air. Two years ago CNBC temporarily
suspended him from appearing on the air after questions arose about
comments he made about a stock that he was trading at the time.
</P>
<P>
   News Corp., the parent company of Fox News, has a 1.6 percent
stake in TheStreet.com. The New York Times also owns 6 percent of
the company and operates a joint newsroom with the Web site.
Co-founder Martin Peretz, owner of The New Republic, has an 11.8
percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   Cramer produces voluminous amounts of commentary about the stock
market in various forms. In addition to his TV appearances and
numerous daily columns on TheStreet.com, he also writes a weekly
column for New York magazine and contributes to Inside.com, a new
media news Web site in which he also has a financial interest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-18-00 0017 </TRAILER>
