<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Heartburn Drug Is Cheaper  </HEADLINE>
By PHIL GALEWITZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- In an unusual step to quickly grab market share
for the world's biggest-selling pills, American Home Products Corp.
is pricing its newest heartburn drug 30 percent below its main
rival.
</P>
<P>
   AHP said Wednesday it has decided to sell wholesale a daily dose
of Protonix for $3 compared to $4.14 for AstraZeneca's Prilosec.
Retail prices typically cost about 20 percent more.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to compete on price is rare in sale of brand-name
drugs. Instead, drug companies typically focus on the effectiveness
of their drugs in sales pitches to doctors and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We analyzed the market and realized we could provide a safe
product and price it less, that not only would make it competitive
but would enable the health care system to realize savings,'' said
Doug Petkus, a spokesman for Madison, N.J.-based American Home.
</P>
<P>
   ''American Home is trying to capture market share in a crowded
market, so this is not an unreasonable strategy,'' said Bob Kirby,
who follows the pharmaceutical industry for the Edward Jones
brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   The gastrointestinal drug market is the biggest prescription
drug category. Prilosec alone had more than $5.9 billion in sales
worldwide last year, more than any other prescription medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Drug prices have become a hot-button political issue this year
as Congress looks to extend prescription drug coverage to Medicare
beneficiaries. Drug manufactures say the cost of their products
reflects the expense of discovering and developing new medicines.
But critics contend many high-priced drugs often are no more
effective than cheaper alternatives, such as generic medicines.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say American Home's pricing decision was based on a
need to quickly become established in the highly competitive market
for heartburn drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, a generic version of Prilosec is expected to be
approved in the United States. Generic drugs typically sell for at
least half the cost of brand-name drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Protonix is also the fourth proton-pump inhibitor to be
introduced in the United States. The drugs work by shutting down
the body's mechanism that causes the secretion of excess stomach
acid.
</P>
<P>
   While Protonix is in the same class as Prilosec, TAP's Prevacid
and Johnson &AMP; Johnson's Aciphex, it has not received government
approval for use in treating as many conditions as the other drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration has approved Protonix for up to
16 weeks of treatments, including use in cases of nighttime
heartburn.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Prilosec, is approved for treatment of heartburn
and for ulcers and related gastrointestinal disorders.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors still could prescribe Protonix for related disorders,
but are less likely to do so when a competing drug already has
federal approval for such treatments, said Kirby.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for AstraZeneca, the maker of Prilosec, said the
extra approved uses of its pill, as well as its history of more
than a decade of use, justifies its price.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-18-00 0017 </TRAILER>
