<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kraft CEO Takes Mattel Top Job  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL WHITE
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. (AP) -- The new chief of Mattel says one of
his top priorities is to reassure employees that the company is
getting back on track.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to financial woes, the world's biggest toymaker has
been hurt by layoffs, primarily in its Learning Company operations,
and the departure of many key executives.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am a very inclusive leader. I am a visible leader,'' said
Robert A. Eckert. ''I want to make sure people know I'm the kind of
person who's going to eat with them in the cafeteria, listen to
their concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Eckert quit as president and CEO of Kraft Foods to accept the
top job at El Segundo-based Mattel.
</P>
<P>
   He replaces Jill Barad, who after three turbulent years left the
company in February.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement sent Mattel shares 13 percent higher on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Eckert, who has four children ages 8 to 21, said he also saw his
stock rise at home.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was a hero throughout my kids' childhood because I had
access to macaroni and cheese and Lunchables'' packaged cold-cut
meals, he said. ''I've really scored some points in the last couple
of days.''
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the task of rebuilding Mattel, most importantly
boosting its battered stock price and lifting depressed earnings
after months of management turmoil and big losses.
</P>
<P>
   Eckert got the job in part because of his success rejuvenating
Kraft brands and introducing successful new products. Although
Mattel's products are different from Kraft's, Eckert finds
similarities in the need to create brand awareness and loyalty in
the consumer marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   He spent 23 years at Kraft, the last three as its top executive.
He frequently had been mentioned as a probable successor to
Geoffrey C. Bible, CEO of Kraft parent Philip Morris Companies Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I want to see in a CEO coming into this business is
someone with some global branding experience ... someone who is
able to implement some operating efficiencies into the business,''
said Anthony N. Gikas, an analyst with U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has turnaround experience, and it looks like he addresses
all these needs. Certainly the credentials are all in place,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel's board did an extensive search looking for a replacement
to Barad, who spent 21 years at the toymaker. She is credited with
building the Barbie brand from a $320 million U.S. business in 1985
to a $2 billion global brand by 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But she left after she reported the company's fourth-straight
quarterly loss, and continued weakness at its Learning Company
division.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel purchased the Learning Company, the maker of Carmen
Sandiego and other software titles, for $3.6 billion earlier in
1999 as part of a bid to strengthen its hand in the growing
interactive toy business. Mattel is now trying to sell the
division.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
