<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bragman seeks to oust fellow Democrat as New York Assembly speaker  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- State Assembly Majority Leader Michael
Bragman says he is moving to oust fellow Democrat Sheldon Silver as
speaker of the chamber and to take over the top job himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not going to fail ... I'm absolutely confident,''
Bragman, a Syracuse-area Democrat, told reporters Wednesday at the
state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said he would formally move against Silver on Monday
when the Assembly reconvenes. The house was briefly in session
Wednesday before Silver sent members home for the week.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Lynch, a spokesman for Manhattan Democrat Silver, said
Bragman lacked the support among the chamber's Democrats to oust
Silver. She also distributed a letter from Silver in which he fired
Bragman ''effective immediately'' as majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an attempted coup that's failing,'' Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Silver supporters agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no constituency in there to change speakers and the
notion that there are a majority of Democrats who want to do that
is hallucinatory,'' said Assemblyman Richard Brodsky of Westchester
County.
</P>
<P>
   But Bragman had his own supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Standing beside him at a hastily convened news conference was
Queens Democratic Chairman Thomas Manton, a former congressman who
has been at odds lately with Silver. Also on hand was state
Assemblyman Martin Luster, an Ithaca Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Manton said he was not concerned about New York City losing
influence in the Assembly where city Democrats have ruled for
years. No Democrat from traditionally more conservative upstate New
York has been Assembly speaker in more than 80 years.
</P>
<P>
   Manton called Bragman a ''straight shooter'' who ''certainly is
very knowledgeable about all our state and our local city issues as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Queens Democratic boss said that ''although I believe Shelly
Silver is a fine man and a fine public servant, I believe he's lost
the confidence of his members.''
</P>
<P>
   Manton said Assembly members had complained to him about ''too
much centralized control'' in the Assembly and that members
couldn't get sufficient publicity for their favorite issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman appeared to play to such complaints as he declared
Wednesday that he wanted ''to make sure this is a member-driven
house.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, should Bragman become the first upstate Democratic
speaker of the Assembly in modern times it could have a significant
impact on the region. Generally, legislative leaders are very
careful to keep their bases of power well stocked with extra
goodies from the state budget.
</P>
<P>
   The halls of the state Capitol were sizzling Wednesday when
initial reports spread that Bragman was on the verge of moving
against Silver, possibly even with the help of opposition
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman, as the leader of the Assembly's conservative upstate
Democrats, has good relations with many Republican members, but he
denied any collusion with them in the attempt to overthrow Silver.
</P>
<P>
   One scenario had Bragman lining up some fellow Democrats who are
dissatisfied with Silver's leadership and some or all of the
chamber's 51 Republican members to come up with the 76 votes needed
in the 150-member Assembly to elect a new speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Relations have been strained between Silver and Bragman for some
time over a host of issues, including Bragman's desire to someday
have Silver's job.
</P>
<P>
   More recently there has been tension over Bragman's decision to
get behind the possible 2002 gubernatorial candidacy of state
Comptroller H. Carl McCall. Silver had urged members to stay
neutral for the time being and there has been speculation that
Silver really favors the potential rival candidacy for governor of
federal Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman was also not among the 24 speakers that addressed the
Democratic state convention Tuesday that nominated Hillary Rodham
Clinton for the U.S. Senate. Silver had much influence over who got
those speaking assignments.
</P>
<P>
   Silver was elected Assembly speaker in 1994. Bragman has been
majority leader that entire time.
</P>
<P>
   The last Albany leader to be deposed was then-state Senate
Majority Leader Ralph Marino, a Long Island Republican, who was
ousted in a 1994 Thanksgiving Day weekend coup led by current
Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, a Rensselaer County Republican. At
the time, Marino's troops insisted Bruno didn't have the votes to
pull off the coup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-18-00 0025 </TRAILER>
