<HEADLINE> Report: Jarvis Offered Wizards Job  </HEADLINE>
By JOSEPH WHITE
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Michael Jordan has offered the Washington
Wizards coaching job to St. John's coach Mike Jarvis, TNT said
Wednesday night, although a team source and the Washington Post
knocked down the report.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, the Wizards' president of basketball operations, has
said he wants a coach in place by Sunday's NBA draft lottery.
</P>
<P>
   TNT cited a source who said negotiations between Jordan and
Jarvis would begin Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   However, a team source, speaking on the condition he not be
identified, told The Associated Press the speculation was premature
and that the team has no plans for an announcement through the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Washington Post reported in Thursday's editions that
Jordan and Jarvis met at length Wednesday, but the job was not
offered, nor were possible terms discussed. The newspaper did cite
several sources who indicated Jordan is close to making an offer.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis, who coached George Washington in the nation's capital
from 1990-98, is one of five known candidates Jordan has been
considering.
</P>
<P>
   Interim coach Darrell Walker and Golden State assistant Rod
Higgins were ruled out Wednesday when Jordan gave them front-office
jobs. Jordan's former Bulls teammate, John Paxson, pulled himself
out of the running recently when he told Jordan he wanted to remain
in the Chicago area.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny Wilkens, the NBA's career leader in coaching victories,
also interviewed with Jordan, but he didn't help his cause last
week when prematurely indicated that Jordan had offered him the
job.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis reportedly was in the Washington area Wednesday. He still
has a home in the Maryland suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis has spent two seasons at St. John's, where he compiled a
53-17 record and took the Red Storm to the NCAA tournament each
year.
</P>
<P>
   At George Washington, Jarvis revitalized the program and in his
first season led the school to its first winning record in eight
years. The Colonials became a regular participant in the NCAA
tournament in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   His task with the Wizards would be more daunting. Washington
hasn't won a playoff game in 12 years and has had four coaches --
Bernie Bickerstaff, Jim Brovelli, Gar Heard and Walker -- in the
last 14 months. The roster includes overpaid veterans Juwan Howard,
Rod Strickland and Mitch Richmond, whose long-term contracts make
it nearly impossible for the team to make major personnel
acquisitions under the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan became the president of basketball operations and a
part-owner of the Wizards on Jan. 19 and has been very aggressive
in his mission to turn the franchise around. He practiced with the
team, fired Heard within a few days and this week restructured the
front-office staff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-18-00 0030 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
