<HEADLINE> Clinton addresses graduates of Coast Guard academy  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) -- The latest class of Coast Guard
officers started their careers with words of support and promises
of more funding from President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's graduation ceremonies at the U.S. Coast Guard
Academy mark the last time Clinton will address a military academy
as their commander in chief.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the graduates they will play a vital role in
combating terrorism and providing global security, in a new age of
biological warfare and cyber terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ''Your class will play an even larger role in defending and
advancing America's security. It is very important to me, as the
commander in chief, that each and every one of you understand the
threats we face, and what we should do to meet them,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would seek $300 million to strengthen
counterterrorism efforts, including increased monitoring of the
Canadian border, expanding forensic examination of forged travel
papers, and new task forces to get local and federal law
enforcement to work together.
</P>
<P>
   The money was part of a strategy to make sure the United States
is ''paying our fair share'' in international affairs, in
cooperation with other nations, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He cited cooperation with Jordan and Canada to catch an alleged
New Year's Eve bombing plot as an example of the kind of
cooperation the country needs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton promised in his new budget $376 million more for the
Coast Guard, including money to buy new ships.
</P>
<P>
   The 190 new Coast Guard officers applauded Clinton's message.
</P>
<P>
   ''To get such support from the president is really wonderful,''
said Hai Dang, a cadet from Escondido, Calif. who will be serving
on a cutter that monitors the Alaskan border with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Per tradition, the graduates gleefully threw their hats and
epaulets in the air at the end of the ceremony as a symbol of
saying goodbye to their cadet life. Children, including students
from New London, ran onto the field to collect the hats and
epaulets.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's half-hour speech, with the Coast Guard cutter Reliance
and the Thames River in the background, included many inside jokes
for cadets. One cadet was a contestant on ''The Price is Right,''
while an instructor had a role on ''Baywatch.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted that the Class of 2000's spirit was so high that
opposing schools complained in writing about the cadets' heckling
at soccer games.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know if any of you got in trouble for that, but
pursuant to long-standing tradition, I hereby grant amnesty to all
candidates marching tours or serving restrictions for such minor
offenses,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   Cadet Asheley Bodkin of Dayton, Va., who will be stationed in
Seattle, said the graduation was a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity
for her.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought it was great thing for him to be our graduation
speaker,'' Bodkin said.
</P>
<P>
   The class includes nine graduates from Connecticut, 64 women and
five international students. One graduate, Nour Kabariti of Jordan,
is the first woman to serve in the Jordanian Navy and the first
Arab to graduate from the academy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-18-00 0102 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
