<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federal Inspectors: UConn researchers mistreated and neglected animals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   STORRS, Conn. (AP) -- The University of Connecticut has been
cited for mistreating and neglecting its research animals following
the death of five rabbits.
</P>
<P>
   Federal inspectors from the U.S. Department of Agriculture found
repeat violations at the university's animal research facility over
the past two years, including rabbits and pigs penned up in hot
cages without drinking water, The Chronicle of Willimantic reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said UConn was fined $4,500 in 1998 for neglecting
its research animals.
</P>
<P>
   A USDA spokeswoman said federal inspectors made an unannounced
visit to the research facility in March and found structurally
unsound cages, dirty water drains, inadequate shelter from
sunlight, and dirty drinking water receptacles, among other
violations. An inspector returned last week and found some of the
problems still had not been addressed, the spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Smith, the university's vice provost for research and
graduate education, told The Chronicle the problems were limited to
just two labs. He said the university is taking steps to see that
the situation is corrected and acknowledged that the latest
violations most probably will result in another fine.
</P>
<P>
   UConn has begun conducting formal training sessions for animal
care technicians and has appointed Herbert E. Whiteley, professor
and head of the department of pathobiology, as interim director of
the Office of Animal Research Services, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The violations and any USDA actions against UConn will not
affect any grants to the animal research center, such as the $5.1
million given by the USDA to the research center in January for the
development of animal vaccines, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an official at Pfizer Inc.'s division of animal
health and biological research told The Chronicle the drug maker
will no longer conduct any animal research projects with UConn
until the university fully complies with the federal Animal Welfare
Act. Randy Leyh, manager of animal and biological research, said
that although the Groton-based company is not involved currently
with any animal research projects with UConn, all future projects
in the animal research area will be suspended until compliance is
met.
</P>
<P>
   UConn currently has approximately 15,000 vertebrate animals, or
about two dozen species, for research purposes. Most of the animals
are rabbits, but there also are cows, goats, pigs, cats, mice and
rats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
