<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Va. warden sues newspapers, officials for defamation  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   The warden of a Virginia prison where nearly 500
Connecticut
inmates have been transferred claims he has been defamed by two
Connecticut lawmakers, the head of the Bridgeport NAACP chapter and
three newspapers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stanley Young, warden of Wallens Ridge State Prison in Big Stone
Gap, Va., filed a federal lawsuit Wednesday. In it, he claims that
the officials' comments and newspaper articles have depicted him as
a racist who ''not only tolerates but encourages abuse by his
guards.''
</P>
<P>
   Named as defendants are state Sen. Alvin Penn, D-Bridgeport;
state Rep. Michael Lawlor, D-East Haven; and Carolyn Nah of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People office
in Bridgeport.
</P>
<P>
   Young also sued the Connecticut Post, the New Haven Advocate and
The Hartford Courant.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who has served as warden of the maximum security prison
since April 1999, is seeking $13.5 million in damages. His lawsuit
was filed Friday in U.S. District Court for the Western District of
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Penn, co-chairman of the Legislature's Public Safety Committee,
said Wednesday the lawsuit was an attempt to divert attention from
allegations of unsafe conditions at the Virginia prison.
</P>
<P>
   Since October, about 480 Connecticut inmates have been housed at
Wallens Ridge. Gov. John G. Rowland and correction officials say
the transfers ease overcrowding in Connecticut prisons and break up
gangs.
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers and inmate advocates say they fear for the safety
of the prisoners, most of whom are minorities. In April, David
Tracy, a 20-year-old inmate from Bridgeport, hung himself in his
cell. In March, three Connecticut inmates were shot with rubber
bullets by guards trying to break up a scuffle.
</P>
<P>
   ''I give as much validity to that lawsuit as I did to the plan
to send inmates down to Virginia,'' said Penn, who wants a bill
that would bring the inmates home to be considered during next
month's special session of the Legislature. ''I never attacked the
man. I attacked the plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Nah was quoted in a Post story which focused on the presence of
Civil War memorabilia in Young's office. She said she never
knowingly made any false statements about the warden.
</P>
<P>
   ''I stand by my comments,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawlor, who said he hadn't seen the lawsuit and could not
comment on its merits, said the move appears to be in reaction to
tough questions from Connecticut lawmakers and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is true about Virginia is they are obviously not
accustomed to being criticized at all,'' he said. ''The idea that a
public official would actually sue legislators or journalists
because he is criticized is an indication someone is not up for the
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Toolan, editor of The Courant, said the paper stood by its
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously we don't believe we have defamed anyone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Sayers, editor and publisher of the Connecticut Post, said
Wednesday he had not seen the lawsuit and could not comment.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Thompson, publisher of the New Haven Advocate, a news and
entertainment weekly, declined to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-18-00 0103 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000518.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asthma emergency sought in Hartford; other cities also worried  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Environmental groups in Hartford are
joining a growing number of officials and experts worried about the
rapid increase in asthma in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The Hartford Environmental Justice Network urged city officials
Wednesday to declare an asthma emergency.
</P>
<P>
   The network cited a recent study by the Connecticut Children's
Medical Center showing the asthma rate in Hartford is more than
five times the national average. More than 7,500 Hartford children
were screened, with 41 percent suffering from doctor-diagnosed
asthma, the coalition said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They can't breath. They can't sleep. They can't eat,'' said
Mercedes Gentles, whose three children have asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Urban areas in Connecticut and around the country have been
hardest hit by asthma.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's frightening,'' said state Rep. Chris Caruso,
D-Bridgeport. ''It's affecting such a large number of the
population.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of Bridgeport children brought to emergency rooms for
asthma is twice the state average, Caruso said. He said lawmakers
must reach a consensus to clean up the state's five worst-polluting
power plants and find ways to curb auto emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Asthma causes obstruction and inflammation of the air passages.
Researchers have not determined why the burden of asthma falls
disproportionately on inner city youths, especially blacks and
Hispanics. But some officials blame environmentally hazardous
projects such as power plants that are often located in cities.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, about 1,400 children under 15 are hospitalized
for asthma annually, while 6,000 visit emergency rooms, according
to the state Department of Public Health. The department is
identifying high risk populations and is educating the public about
treatment and reducing environmental conditions that may contribute
to asthma attacks, said spokesman William Gerrish.
</P>
<P>
   ''Certainly asthma is a priority for us,'' Gerrish said.
</P>
<P>
   About 5,000 to 10,000 Americans die annually from asthma, said
Jack Elias, chief of pulmonary and critical care at Yale University
School of Medicine. The disease costs billions of dollars annually
in lost productivity and care and is the number one cause of school
absenteeism, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's an epidemic,'' Elias said. ''To have a disease
that is this common should be very alarming to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   A new study by the Pew Environmental Health Commission says the
country should declare a war on asthma.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel that war should begin here first,'' said Dr. Mark
Mitchell, president of the Connecticut Coalition for Environmental
Justice. ''We feel our urban population are the canaries in the
cage. It's coming here first.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell and others want a federal study to determine why the
asthma rate is so high in Hartford. Councilwoman Elizabeth Horton
Sheff promised to support the Network's goals before the council.
</P>
<P>
   New Haven-based Connecticut Voices For Children reported that
one in three Hartford children had asthma in 1994, up from one in
five in 1980. The group cited a 1996 survey indicating that 22
percent of New Haven students were told by a doctor they had
asthma.
</P>
<P>
   In Stamford, officials are looking at geographic data to
determine areas where asthma is concentrated, said Anthony Iton,
the city's health director. The next step will be to increase
education and inspect rental properties to determine if conditions
are triggering asthma.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a significant concern,'' Iton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
