<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rowland executive order designed to curb pollution  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNE YOUMANS
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- An executive order designed to cut
emissions from state power plants is being blasted by
environmentalists and lawmakers who unsuccessfully pushed for
stricter pollution regulations in the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John G. Rowland on Wednesday issued the order that requires
the state Department of Environmental Protection to develop
regulations to reduce the emission of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen
oxides at 61 power plants. The regulations must be in place by May
1, 2003.
</P>
<P>
   But critics said it sets no firm deadlines for implementing
those regulations and lets the state's worst polluters off too
easily.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governor and those lawmakers who decided to put big
business profit over the health of the state are now trying to use
this order to cover their deeds,'' said state Rep. Christopher
Caruso, D-Bridgeport. ''The executive order does absolutely
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan covers fossil fuel-fired power plants and large
industrial and commercial boilers, not just the so-called ''Filthy
Five'' plants targeted by the failed legislation. The plants would
be allowed to trade emission ''credits'' from lesser polluters in
an effort to reduce overall smog.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said the plan-- put together by lawmakers, utility
regulators and environmental officials -- would cut the emission of
sulfur dioxide by 30 percent and nitrogen oxides by 20 percent by
the summer of 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters said the plan cuts air pollution while ensuring
Connecticut has enough power to get through another hot summer.
Utility customers also would not have to pay higher prices, at
least until the first price freezes of deregulation end in December
2003.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people of Connecticut will benefit from cleaner air, but
they'll do so in a way that will keep the lights on and not
needlessly bankrupt companies,'' said Sen. Thomas Herlihy,
R-Simsbury, ranking member of the Legislature's Energy and
Technology Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers said they will draw up a plan of their own, one
that includes clean air advocates they say were shut out of
Rowland's measure. Caruso hopes to revisit the issue in a special
legislative session next month.
</P>
<P>
   ''The legislative working group still will meet, in the interest
of bringing all the stakeholders to the table to resolve, once and
for all, this important environmental issue,'' House Speaker Moira
Lyons, D-Stamford, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   For the past three years, environmentalists have fought for a
reduction in nitrogen and sulfur oxide levels at plants in Norwalk,
Bridgeport, New Haven, Middletown and Montville.
</P>
<P>
   Facing the loss of hundreds of millions of dollars if the plants
were forced to shut down, the power companies launched a feverish
lobbying campaign at the Capitol that prevailed two weeks ago when
no cleanup action was taken.
</P>
<P>
   Clean-air advocates had pushed for legislation that would have
required reduced emissions by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's simply buying more and more time and doing what the
industry wants,'' said Betty McLaughlin, an advocate with the
Connecticut Coalition for Clean Air. ''Three years to write
regulations is three years of doing nothing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
