<HEADLINE> Women Rise To Power in Taiwan  </HEADLINE>
By ANNIE HUANG
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- When Taiwan's newly elected vice president
stepped out of a black limousine and faced a long line of generals,
the men looked bewildered and hesitated for a moment before raising
their hands in a crisp salute.
</P>
<P>
   The awkward response to Annette Lu was understandable: The brass
was saluting a female leader for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of other Taiwanese men in the military and government are
going to have to get used to showing more respect to women. Keeping
his campaign promise to promote more women, President-elect Chen
Shui-bian has filled about a quarter of the top posts in his
Cabinet with females, a total of eight.
</P>
<P>
   It was an unusual move for a leader in chauvinistic Asia, where
-- much more so than in the West -- men still have a tight grip on
the best jobs in government and business.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a milestone for Taiwanese women,'' said Chen Chu, the
newly appointed Labor Council chief, the first woman to lead the
Cabinet agency.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Asian women who followed their husbands or fathers into
politics -- such as former Philippine President Corazon Aquino and
India's late Prime Minister Indira Gandhi -- the Taiwanese women
rose to prominence the hard way: marching in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Lu and Chen Chu both took part in the democracy movement that in
1987 helped end decades of repressive martial law in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   They were convicted of sedition and sentenced to jail in 1979,
along with six male dissidents. Lu was jailed for 5{ years and Chen
six years before they were paroled.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was a conservative, traditional society where women had
no say in things,'' Chen Chu, 50, said. ''Even most men were too
afraid to support the opposition movement, but we had quite a few
very brave women.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen Chu, chief of social affairs in Taiwan's second-largest
city, Kaohsiung, said she was influenced by family members who were
staunch supporters of the dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   The end of martial law in Taiwan gave rise to a vocal and
powerful feminist movement. As many women as men now enter college,
and many women hold key positions in private businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But working women are still a minority. While 70 percent of
Taiwanese men work, only 45 percent of women do so, less than the
50 percent average among Japanese and Korean women.
</P>
<P>
   In the national legislature, women hold 43 of the 225 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the new female Cabinet ministers hold prominent
positions, rather than the token jobs awarded to women in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Yeh Chu-lan, a lawmaker, will be Taiwan's first female
transportation minister. Taiwan also will have its first government
spokeswoman, economist Chung Chin.
</P>
<P>
   Another post, head of the Mainland Affairs Council that handles
the delicate relations with China, went to Tsai Ying-wen. Tsai, who
holds a doctorate in law from the University of London, has been a
key negotiator in pushing for Taiwan's entrance to the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   But another battle for equality may have just begun as the women
are tested for their capability to run the government.
</P>
<P>
   Lu, Taiwan's first female vice president, has complained that
male politicians expected her to be powerless and remain
''voiceless.''
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's constitution simply states the vice president shall act
for the president when the leader cannot perform his duties without
saying what the job actually involves.
</P>
<P>
   Lu loudly questioned whether that meant she should be a ''flower
vase.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Many men still don't accept women as their equals, and it is
more so the closer you get to the nucleus (top echelon) of power,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   With a master's degree in law from Harvard, Lu, 56, won a seat
in the national legislature and was elected chief of Taoyuan County
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Many men said Lu's comments about her new job reinforced the
perception that women lack political dexterity, but feminists
praised her for speaking out.
</P>
<P>
   ''Women have no power in this society. If they speak softly, how
can they gain any power?'' asked TV anchorwoman Sisy Chen.
</P>
<P>
   Chen Chu, however, said she never gained any privilege as a
woman and was never suppressed because of it, either.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, Lu, and Tsai have never married, reflecting a society
where many women must choose between a promising career and getting
married, which could involve more family commitments.
</P>
<P>
   ''Women face too many roadblocks,'' Lu said. ''They have to work
several times harder than men.''
</P>
<P>
   Feminists say they expect the new government to set up more
childcare centers and old-age homes to relieve the household
burdens that fall mostly on women.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
