<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Evaluates 1st Year in Office  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE COPANS
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Pulling a shiny card of campaign promises out
from his chest pocket, Prime Minister Ehud Barak tried to rekindle
the national euphoria that surrounded his election one year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly acknowledging the doubts about Israel's progress that
have surfaced of late but determined to squash them, Barak pounded
his fist in the air Wednesday as he brandished the card of pledges.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are a government that does not deal with niceties of
language and packaging, it deals with action,'' he said. ''I have
no doubt that ... we will continue on this path and, in the end,
the feeling will change as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak's landslide victory over former Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu last May 17 boosted expectations in Israel and abroad
that real progress on all fronts in the peace process was just
around the corner. But the luster has begun to fade.
</P>
<P>
   With Israeli-Palestinian talks lagging and no sign that
negotiations with Syria will be resumed, Barak is behind in his own
plans to be well on the way to ending Arab-Israeli conflict by this
point.
</P>
<P>
   And just as Israeli and Palestinian negotiators delve into the
thorniest issues dividing the sides, Barak's coalition has begun to
crack over his peace policies.
</P>
<P>
   However, he is fulfilling one of his key campaign commitments:
The army has started to withdraw troops from south Lebanon to end
Israel's 18-year presence there by July 7.
</P>
<P>
   But the absence of an arrangement with Syria, the main power
broker in Lebanon, could lead to trouble. Residents along the
border complain nightly on national television about fears that
they will be subject to guerrilla attacks after the pullout when
the border will be just yards from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Barak has fallen behind in promises to pull Israel
out of a recession and create hundreds of thousands of new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis elected Barak mostly for his centrist policies on the
peace process, but they are beginning to express skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent poll, Israelis gave the former chief of the army a
28 percent approval rating -- lower than Netanyahu's support a year
into office.
</P>
<P>
   ''His approval rating is the lowest it's ever been,'' said
pollster Hanoch Smith. ''There is major uncertainty about whether
or not he's headed for peace with the Syrians and the Palestinians.
It's not clear which way he's going since things are stuck.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 500 Israelis had a margin of error of 1.5 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   A second deadline for the broad outlines of a final peace treaty
between Israel and the Palestinians passed on May 13 with both
sides acknowledging they were far from agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. envoy Dennis Ross said this week that he has complete
confidence in the Israeli leader.
</P>
<P>
   ''Prime Minister Barak has made it clear that he sees an
opportunity to end what has been an intractable conflict,'' Ross
told reporters. ''I believe that he is determined to press ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barak's coalition has begun to crumble. One of the largest
partners in the government, the ultra-Orthodox Shas party, has
threatened to pull out if it doesn't receive funds for its troubled
education network.
</P>
<P>
   One other key ally, the National Religious Party, has already
announced it is quitting the government over Barak's peace policies
and an immigrant party, Israel B'Aliya, stands poised to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare show of political boldness, Barak managed to push one
of his peace initiatives through parliament on Tuesday -- commanding
the support of even some of his more hesitant coalition partners by
making the vote a motion of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yesterday, only yesterday, did Barak begin his real term as
prime minister,'' commentator Nahum Barnea wrote in the Yediot
Ahronot newspaper Wednesday. ''He spent a year dancing. The issues
that have been tearing at Israel for years seemed to have passed
him by.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-18-00 0156 </TRAILER>
