<HEADLINE> Car service driver killed in Bronx  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A car service driver found on the ground next to
his vehicle in the Bronx died minutes after being taken to the
hospital, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The driver, identified as Kim Hong, was not a licensed livery
cab driver and worked for a car service not licensed with the Taxi
&AMP; Limousine Commission. But an advocate for drivers says the killer
did not know that, so Hong's murder on Wednesday makes him the 10th
driver slain on duty this year. Eleven drivers were killed in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were out to kill a livery cab driver,'' said Fernando
Mateo, president of the New York State Federation of Taxi Drivers.
</P>
<P>
   So far, police have no suspects. Robbery appeared to be the
motive -- some of Hong's property was removed -- but police did not
say what was taken.
</P>
<P>
   Hong, 20, was found shortly after midnight after police received
a call about a car accident in the Williamsbridge section of the
Bronx. They found Hong's black Acura Legend had hit an unoccupied
parked car, and Hong was discovered next to it with a gunshot wound
to his back.
</P>
<P>
   He was taken to Montefiore Hospital where he was pronounced dead
at 12:35 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Hong, who was from Cambodia, worked for Preferred Car Company in
the Bronx and had been dispatched to pick up a client, police said.
He is survived by his pregnant wife and their 2-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   Police have already formed a task force to combat a recent rash
of livery cab driver killings and the TLC has started requiring all
drivers to install either bulletproof partitions or security
cameras in their cars. The city set aside $5 million to help pay
for the extra security measures.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings echo the early 1990s, when livery cab drivers were
under siege. In 1992, cabbies were killed at the rate of nearly one
per week for a record annual total of 45 slayings.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, in March and April of 1990, seven livery drivers
were killed in six weeks, prompting scores of drivers to quit or
switch to day shifts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-18-00 0158 </TRAILER>
