<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Koreas Agree on Summit Talks Agenda  </HEADLINE>
By SANG-HUN CHOE
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) -- South Korea and North Korea reached full
agreement Thursday on the agenda and other details for a summit of
their leaders in June, negotiators from both sides said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement came after negotiators met at the border village
of Panmunjom and resolved one last pending issue -- the size of the
South Korean press corp for the June 12-14 summit in the North's
capital, Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   The summit would be the first ever between the two Koreas, which
were divided into the communist North and the pro-Western South in
1945. Their three-year war in the early 1950s ended in an
armistice, not a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Park Jae-kyu, South Korea's unification minister, said an
advance party of South Korean officials will visit Pyongyang at the
end of May to prepare for the summit. The 30-member team will
include specialists in security, protocol and communications.
</P>
<P>
   North Korean negotiator Choi Sung Ik said both sides agreed to a
broadly worded agenda that calls for self-reliance, peace and
national unity. South Korea had dropped its proposal for a specific
agenda listing matters such as economic aid to the impoverished
North.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's Cabinet-level meeting at Panmunjom was the fifth
since April 22. After four rounds of talks, the two sides last week
decided to discuss details through documents and telephone
contacts.
</P>
<P>
   In a compromise, South Korea agreed to send a delegation of 130
officials as well as a 50-member press corps, down from its
proposal of 80 journalists. North Korea, which has often accused
South Korean and Western journalists of biased reporting, had asked
that the number be halved.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea agreed to allow South Korean journalists to hold
live television broadcasts from Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean President Kim Dae-jung and North Korean leader Kim
Jong Il will meet at least two or three times and more if
necessary, according to the 15-point agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators agreed that there will be no markings or signs at
the meeting site or conference rooms. South Korean officials said
that meant there will be no display of national flags or symbols in
an effort to avoid ideological friction.
</P>
<P>
   In a luncheon meeting with religious leaders on Wednesday,
President Kim Dae-jung said he would not seek ''too much at a
time'' from the summit with North Korean leader Kim Jong Il.
</P>
<P>
   High on South Korea's summit agenda are economic cooperation and
reunions of separated family members. North Korea is expected to
raise the U.S. military presence in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean officials believe North Korea was driven to agree
to the summit for economic reasons. With its economy in tatters,
the North has been relying on foreign aid to feed its 22 million
people since 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-18-00 0159 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
