<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Columbia Seeks Patent Extension  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Three decades ago, Columbia University
undergraduate Judd Gregg prowled the sidelines of sports events as
the school's mascot, clad as a lion. Now a U.S. senator, Gregg is
still showing school spirit.
</P>
<P>
   The New Hampshire Republican, Columbia Class of '69, has
inserted a provision into an agriculture spending bill that would
help his alma mater win a lucrative patent extension on a process
its scientists invented for making some widely sold biotechnology
drugs. The patent, which nets Columbia up to $100 million a year in
royalties from companies using the procedure, otherwise expires in
August.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg's provision has set off a wave of protest from the
pharmaceutical industry. Many companies would like to use the
process without paying royalties, while others worry that their
competitors would be emboldened by a Columbia victory to try
extending patents on other products or processes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We find it to be a very, very dangerous precedent and
potentially costly for consumers,'' said G. Thomas Long, counsel
for the National Pharmaceutical Alliance, which represents
manufacturers and marketers of generic drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg and Columbia officials counter that inventors of drugs can
apply for patent extensions, so it is only fair that the law be
changed to let inventors of processes do the same thing. Besides,
they say, the university uses most of the royalties for research
that benefits everyone.
</P>
<P>
   If Columbia stops collecting royalties from companies, ''Do you
honestly think they'll reduce their prices for these products?''
Gregg said.
</P>
<P>
   The 350-word provision, which does not mention Columbia by name,
is typical of the hundreds of special-interest items lawmakers
shoehorn into Congress' 13 must-pass spending bills each year.
</P>
<P>
   As a subcommittee chairman on the Senate Appropriations
Committee, which writes spending measures, Gregg is well-placed to
insert such a provision. And many colleagues are reluctant to
challenge a chairman's project -- especially one like the sometimes
bristly Gregg -- knowing they might need a favor from him later.
</P>
<P>
   But some observers are criticizing the arrangement because the
school used its relationship with Gregg to influence legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we're really talking about is special access ... that
would not be available to just anyone,'' said Peter Eisner,
managing director of the Center for Public Integrity, a nonpartisan
watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg says he was asked to address the problem by his friend
George Rupp, Columbia's president. He says he sees nothing wrong
with that and put it into the spending bill -- which may move
relatively quickly through Congress -- because Columbia needs the
law changed before its patent lapses.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess Mr. Eisner wants a windfall profit for the drug
companies at the expense of a research university,'' Gregg said.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia got its patent for a technique called cotransformation
in August 1983, making it one of the earlier biotechnology
processes. Using it, a gene can be inserted into a cell so that
cell will produce proteins used in medicines.
</P>
<P>
   Since the process was introduced, Columbia says sales of drugs
produced by cotransformation have totaled $28.3 billion, on which
the school has taken an average 1 percent royalty.
</P>
<P>
   The school produces no drugs itself, but has granted licenses to
34 companies that make and market 18 pharmaceuticals. The drugs
include Activase for heart attack and stroke victims; Herceptin for
breast cancer; and Avonex for multiple sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   Three Columbia scientists developed the procedure using grants
from the federal National Institutes of Health that totaled ''the
low millions of dollars over many years,'' said Michael Crow,
executive vice president and provost at Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The three inventors split 20 percent of the royalties, he said,
so each reaps millions annually. The rest -- minus some
administrative costs -- goes to research.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not like we're taking the money and buying hotels,'' said
Crow.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg's language would let nonprofit organizations that have
invented processes that have led to five new drugs apply to extend
their patents.
</P>
<P>
   Crow says it was written ''in generic form'' and could affect
others. Critics say Columbia is the only entity they know of that
would qualify, and that Columbia would meet every criteria
established, virtually guaranteeing a patent extension.
</P>
<P>
   The provision was initially drafted by Columbia lawyers but
altered with suggestions from lawmakers and aides, Crow said.
</P>
<P>
   Crow said Columbia would seek a five-year extension, the maximum
drug inventors can now get to prolong patents. But under a formula
in current law the school expects an extension lasting 1{ years, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects for enactment are unclear. The $75 billion agriculture
appropriations bill has been approved by the Senate Appropriations
Committee and is awaiting Senate floor action. But the Clinton
administration is expected to come out against the Columbia
provision soon, according to congressional aides speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., whose state is home to some
major drug manufacturers, said he will try to strip the provision
from the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you believe in the market and competition, at some points
monopoly rights have to end,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Eds: The bill is S. 2536.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
