<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angels 8, Orioles 7  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Scott Spiezio singled home the winning
run with one out in the ninth inning and the Anaheim Angels rallied
past Baltimore 8-7 Wednesday night, the Orioles' eighth loss in
nine games.
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad's two-run single in the Angels eighth tied it at 7.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Timlin (0-1) walked Tim Salmon to lead off the ninth and
Garret Anderson sacrificed. After Troy Glaus was intentionally
walked, Spiezio won it with a broken-bat single to center.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Percival (1-2) earned the victory with an inning of hitless
relief, despite walking three batters.
</P>
<P>
   After Buddy Groom escaped a bases-loaded jam in the seventh,
Timlin relieved him with runners at the corners and one out in the
eighth. He walked pinch-hitter Orlando Palmeiro with his first four
pitches and Erstad grounded the next pitch to left field.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken, starting at third base after missing four games
because of scar tissue inflammation in his back, hit an RBI double
in the first inning for the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Belle drove in three runs for Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Rapp, who lasted only 3 1-3 innings last Thursday against
Boston, overcame a shaky first inning. He pitched six innings and
gave up four runs and five hits, including Glaus' 11th homer.
</P>
<P>
   After blowing a three-run margin as quickly as they built it,
the Orioles regained the lead in the second inning on a
bases-loaded, two-run infield single by Belle off Scott
Schoeneweis.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs and the runners moving on a 3-2 pitch, Glaus
charged Belle's slow-hit grounder to third and failed to make the
barehanded pickup as Rich Amaral hustled home right behind Charles
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles added an unearned run in the sixth when B.J. Surhoff
walked, stole second and scored on Glaus' error.
</P>
<P>
   After Glaus homered in the bottom half, Delino DeShields led off
the seventh with a double and scored on Jeff Conine's sacrifice fly
to give Baltimore a 7-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Conine and Ripken hit two-out, RBI doubles in the first after
Belle's sacrifice fly. The Angels tied it in the bottom half with
the help of some sloppy defense by the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Belle and Brady Anderson did not communicate on a fly to
right-center by Erstad and the ball fell between them for a double.
Adam Kennedy doubled home Erstad and scored when Conine, making his
14th consecutive start at first base for the injured Will Clark,
played Mo Vaughn's routine grounder into a two-base error. Vaughn
came home on Tim Salmon's double off the right field wall.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Ripken grounded into a double play for the 328th time in his
20-year career, tying the major league record set by Hank Aaron.
... Keith Luuloa, who was promoted from the Angels' Triple-A
Edmonton club after Tuesday night's game, made his major league
debut as a pinch-runner for Bengie Molina and scored a run. Luuloa
joined Onan Masaoka of the Dodgers and Benny Agbayani of the Mets
as the only current Hawaiian-born players in the majors. ... Rapp
outlasted Benji Gil in a 15-pitch duel, striking him out in the
fourth inning after nine consecutive fouls. ... Tim Belcher, who
hasn't pitched for the Angels since undergoing surgery on his right
elbow on Dec. 2, threw off a mound for 10 minutes on Wednesday (all
fastballs) and reported no discomfort. He'll repeat the routine on
Saturday. ... Rapp and Schoeneweis combined to throw 100 pitches
during the first two innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-18-00 0224 </TRAILER>
