<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ways To Beat Fusaichi Pegasus  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD ROSENBLATT
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Bob Baffert has the problem of how to beat
Fusaichi Pegasus in the Preakness all figured out.
</P>
<P>
   The trainer, with an opinion on nearly everything, has a few
bright ideas on how to outfox the Kentucky Derby winner in
Saturday's $1 million Preakness Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   --Load him in the starting gate backwards.
</P>
<P>
   --Give everyone else a head start.
</P>
<P>
   --Force him to break from behind the starting gate.
</P>
<P>
   --Call in the Stanford band.
</P>
<P>
   The way Fusaichi Pegasus is going, it just might take something
along those lines for any of his seven challengers to stand a
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ''This Derby winner is an extraordinary horse,'' said Baffert,
who sends out Captain Steve in the 1 3-16th-mile Preakness. ''These
other horses are going to have to run the race of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the 18 trainers who sent their 3-year-olds against
Fusaichi Pegasus -- FuPeg for short -- in the Derby, Baffert feels
this Derby winner has what it takes to win the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   ''And my job is to make sure he earns it,'' said Baffert, who
hit the Derby-Preakness double with Silver Charm in 1997 and Real
Quiet in '98. ''We're here to keep him honest.''
</P>
<P>
   Captain Steve, eighth in the Derby, but contending at the top of
the stretch before being bumped by Wheelaway, isn't alone.
</P>
<P>
   A field of eight was entered Wednesday night for the second leg
of the Triple Crown. As expected, Fusaichi Pegasus is the 3-5
favorite in the morning line, with Red Bullet the second choice at
9-2. The Derby winner will be ridden again by Kent Desormeaux;
Jerry Bailey will be aboard Red Bullet.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is fairly straightforward,'' FuPeg trainer Neil Drysdale
said after he selected the No. 7 post for his $4 million colt.
''The horse is quite versatile, and with a quarter-mile to the
first turn and an eight-horse field, the draw isn't that
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Bullet won the Gotham Stakes before being soundly beaten by
FuPeg in the Wood Memorial on April 15. The lightly raced Red
Bullet, trained by Joe Orseno, skipped the Derby. The Preakness
will be his fifth career start.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's done very well here and handles the track well,'' Orseno
said before gaining the No. 1 choice in the post position draw and
choosing post No. 4.
</P>
<P>
   The last non-Derby starter to win the Preakness was Deputed
Testamony in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Other non-Derby starters in the field are Snuck In, at 12-1, and
Hugh Hefner, at 20-1. Four Derby starters are back to try again --
Captain Steve and Impeachment, both at 8-1; High Yield at 10-1 and
Hal's Hope at 20-1.
</P>
<P>
   In the Derby, Impeachment was third, Captain Steve eighth, High
Yield 15th and Hal's Hope 16th.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, FuPeg finally shipped in from Kentucky and
was vanned to Pimlico from the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ''No problem. He traveled well. He's fine,'' Drysdale said,
adding that the playful colt was ''feeling good'' on the van ride
to the track.
</P>
<P>
   FuPeg, accompanied by his personal ''pony'' Bodyguard, was the
first horse off the van and was quickly led down the ramp and into
Barn 7 on the backstretch -- far removed from the Stakes Barn, the
traditional home of the Preakness starters.
</P>
<P>
   The last Derby winner who ran in the Preakness but did not stay
in the Stakes Barn was Northern Dancer in 1964. He won the race
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale chose to keep the frisky Fusaichi Pegasus away from the
media horde hanging around the Stakes Barn because ''it's quieter
back here.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Churchill Downs, where the Derby horses are spread out
and have lots of room to graze, the Pimlico backstretch has 10 long
brick barns, asphalt roads and virtually no grazing space.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Drysdale insists FuPeg will be better off away from
the other Preakness starters.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're here because it's quiet,'' he said. ''And it's less
crowded.''
</P>
<P>
   It'll be noisy and crowded on Saturday, when about 100,000
people show up to see if Fusaichi Pegasus -- FuPeg for short -- can
win the Preakness and earn a chance to become the 12th Triple Crown
winner by taking the Belmont Stakes on June 10.
</P>
<P>
   If he does, his Japanese owner, Fusao Sekiguchi, will collect a
$5 million bonus from Visa USA.
</P>
<P>
   The past three years has produced a Belmont Stakes with the
Triple Crown on the line: Charismatic in '99; Real Quiet in '98 and
Silver Charm in '97. All three fell short in the Belmont. The last
Triple Crown winner was Affirmed in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus soared to the top of his class by beating the
best in the West and then displaying powerful finishing kicks to
take the Wood at Aqueduct and the Derby at Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   Add a five-race winning streak and a quirky personality that has
seen him buck, rear and even throw an exercise rider into the mix,
and horse racing has itself a superhorse in the making.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale, of course, isn't buying any of the hype, especially
when he's told FuPeg looks like a lock in the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can always lose, 100, 200, 300 ways,'' he said. Asked
which horse he feared most on Saturday, Drysdale said, ''I fear all
horses. I'm always worried. I think it's a strong bunch of
3-year-olds this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Baffert has a much different approach than Drysdale,
the white-haired trainer can understand Drysdale's decision to keep
Fusaichi Pegasus away from the hustle and bustle.
</P>
<P>
   ''Neil is a private person, and he knows clicks of cameras are a
distraction to his horse,'' Baffert said. ''He's just protecting
him, and I don't really blame him. Me, I like to share my horses
with everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention a few whimsical ideas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-18-00 0247 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
