<DOCNO> APW20000518.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 02:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bourque Is Back for Game Three  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN MOSSMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Eighteen days after going down with a knee injury,
Colorado Avalanche star defenseman Ray Bourque will return for Game
3 of the Western Conference finals with the Dallas Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque pronounced himself ready to play after a hard practice
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado coach Bob Hartley, who hinted at Bourque's possible
return a day earlier, wasn't available to confirm it. But who would
dare argue with a future Hall of Famer who boasts an NHL-record 403
goals as a defenseman?
</P>
<P>
   Bourque's return for Friday night's game here -- where Colorado
is 6-0 this postseason -- should help the Avalanche compensate for
the loss of another valuable defenseman, Adam Foote, who has been
ruled out of Game 3. Foote sustained an eye injury Monday night in
a 3-2 loss to the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas' victory squared the best-of-seven series 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago in the conference finals, Dallas and Colorado also
were tied 1-1. The Stars won that series in seven games en route to
capturing the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, who has missed the last four playoff games with a
strained left knee, took contact for the first time in Wednesday's
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ''It felt good,'' Bourque said. ''I went through practice and it
went very well. I'm where I need to be. So it's a go for Friday,
and I'm anxious to get going.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, injured in the third game against Detroit on May 1,
skated on his own following the injury and rejoined his teammates
during workouts late last week. Wednesday's practice was a
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ''I did everything,'' he said. ''I did a lot of one-on-ones, a
lot of grinding in the corners. I felt very good.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've kind of turned the corner, and that's what I've waited
for over the last week or so.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bourque insisted he was returning to the ice on his own
timetable, not because Foote is sidelined.
</P>
<P>
   ''Regardless of whether Adam was there or not, you've got to be
good enough to go,'' Bourque said. ''That's why I'm playing Friday,
because I'm well enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Paired together, Bourque and Foote were a force earlier in the
playoffs. Even without Bourque, Foote shut down Dallas' Mike Modano
in a 2-0 victory in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   With Foote exiting early in Game 2, Modano found more room to
skate and scored two goals.
</P>
<P>
   Now Bourque will accept the burden.
</P>
<P>
   ''Adam is a warrior and he's a big part of this team,'' Bourque
said. ''The good thing is the injury could have been worse, and
he'll be back. When, exactly, we're not sure. But we've just got to
hold the fort.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've shown on many occasions in the last month or so how much
heart this team has in picking up the slack whenever somebody has
gone down.''
</P>
<P>
   From the time they acquired Bourque from Boston until his
injury, the Avalanche were 18-3-1. Although there were many anxious
moments when Bourque was hurt, the Avs went 3-1 without him.
</P>
<P>
   Now they face the same challenge without Foote, but this is
clearly a team with imposing depth.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not a one- or two-man team,'' said defenseman Aaron
Miller, who likely will be paired with Bourque on Friday night.
''Adam is a great player, but there's a lot of talent on this team.
Among 20 guys, you can certainly pick up the slack.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-18-00 0253 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000518.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man accused in firebombing hoax found unfit to stand trial  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NORWALK, Conn. (AP) -- A man accused of planting two firebombs at
a Norwalk synagogue has been found incompetent to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Eddie Rodriguez Jr. on Wednesday ordered Joseph Yellen,
35, to spend 60 days at the Connecticut Valley Hospital in
Middletown.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Yellen placed two glass bottles filled with a
flammable liquid and stuffed with rags on the lawn of Congregation
Beth El on Nov. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Yellen told police he chased two men who were about to throw the
devices at the synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested Yellen on Nov. 26, saying he made up the story
in the hope of receiving a lighter sentence in an unrelated court
case. He was charged with falsely reporting an incident. He was
later charged with two felony counts of manufacturing a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   When Yellen's attorney, William Pelletreau, told him of the
judge's order Wednesday, Yellen seemed confused and began screaming
at Prosecutor Robert Katz.
</P>
<P>
   ''You satisfied, Katz?'' Yellen said. ''You piece of garbage.
You throw 20 charges against the wall. You get one that sticks.
This is a comedy act.''
</P>
<P>
   Yellen, who was unshaven and wearing jeans and a black jacket,
brought a duffel bag filled with personal items. Before the
hearing, he said, ''I brought my bag because they are sending me
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Padilla, a social worker with the Department of Mental
Health and Addiction Services, testified that Yellen has been
diagnosed with bipolar disorder with psychotic features.
</P>
<P>
   Padilla said he concluded that Yellen is ''unable to understand
the charges against him and unable to assist in his defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Padilla said Yellen reported that he had been hearing voices of
a self-deprecating nature. He said evaluators attributed some of
his behavior to pervasive paranoia.
</P>
<P>
   Yellen felt that he was being persecuted by members of the
Norwalk Police Department, Padilla said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He thinks they are trying to clean up problems in town by
making him a scapegoat,'' Padilla said.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions in Norwalk were heightened at the time of the incident
because a package of medical waste with anti-Semitic messages
attached to it had been left at the synagogue last August.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Jay Lorenz, a medical waste disposal equipment salesman,
was charged in February with carrying out the crime and similar
incidents in Stamford.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
