<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 03:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US: Surveillance of Embassies Common  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- State Department officials are wondering who
are all those people who stake out American diplomatic missions
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. surveillance detection teams have uncovered more than 700
incidents of suspected monitoring of American personnel and
facilities since the program began in January 1999, a top State
Department official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   That's an average of more than one incident a day.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Secretary of State David Carpenter told a House
committee that the teams were deployed after the State Department
concluded that surveillance against U.S. facilities is intense
prior to an attack.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter spoke to a House International Relations Committee
hearing that was convened to hear a progress report on the embassy
security situation.
</P>
<P>
   That issue has received high priority since the bombings of two
U.S. embassies in East Africa in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   State Department Inspector General Jaquelyn Williams-Bridgers,
who also testified, said U.S. officials are trying to collect
information about the various groups which have had U.S. facilities
under surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter said the presence of the teams has expanded the
security perimeter and the zone of control beyond previous
limitations.
</P>
<P>
   The program is still a work in progress, he said, adding that
the Clinton administration nonetheless believes that ''it is
destined to become a major aspect of our overseas security
defenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter said the surveillance detection teams are no
substitute for having a minimum 100-foot buffer between an official
facility and the nearest street.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until we can build embassies meeting the setback and other
security standards, our efforts cannot provide the degree of
security all of us want for our people and facilities,'' Carpenter
said.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Kennedy, assistant secretary of state for
administration, said a record $800 million was obligated in the
last fiscal year on embassy security, but much remains to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fully 85 percent of our facilities do not meet minimum
security standards,'' he said. ''Some are seriously overcrowded.
Most, however, have to be replaced. ... Our goal is to
expeditiously locate into safe facilities more than 22,000 embassy
staff in over 220 vulnerable buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said that over the past year and a half, 87 properties
at 25 posts have been acquired to expand buffer zones around U.S.
installations.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are looking into the possibility of acquiring an
additional 31 properties at 14 posts, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
