<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 03:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House, Senate Panels OK China Bill  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration and its
congressional allies are buoyed by lopsided committee votes in both
the House and the Senate for a landmark China trade bill. But they
caution that next week's House showdown remains close.
</P>
<P>
   ''This thing is not over by any means,'' said Rep. Robert
Matsui, D-Calif., the administration's point man for the bill among
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton welcomed Wednesday's 34-4 vote by the House
Ways and Means Committee and 18-1 vote by the Senate Finance
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''The strong bipartisan votes in both committees send a clear,
strong message that permanent normal trade relations for China is
vital to America's prosperity at home, our leadership in the world
and to positive change in China,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pledged to redouble his efforts to build support for the
legislation in advance of the House vote.
</P>
<P>
   The president is considering a five-minute address to the nation
on Sunday evening to promote the bill, congressional supporters of
the legislation said.
</P>
<P>
   The near-unanimous Senate committee vote was expected because
bipartisan support for the overall measure has always been broad in
that chamber.
</P>
<P>
   But organized labor has waged a fierce campaign against the
measure, cutting deeply into potential Democratic support in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, at least five Democrats on the Ways and Means Committee
who previously said they were undecided voted for the China-trade
bill on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a good vote. It advanced us,'' said Matsui. ''On the
other hand, the floor will be very difficult next week. There is no
magic bullet.''
</P>
<P>
   Matsui, who earlier predicted that 70-80 of the House's 211
Democrats would support the bill, said Wednesday that his most
realistic hope now was ''closer to 70.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders say they expect about 140 Republicans
to vote for the bill and that Democrats will have to provide the
rest. Since the bill requires 218 affirmative votes if all 435
members vote, that suggests that 78 or more Democratic votes would
be needed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not quite there but we think at the end of the day,
members of Congress will do the right thing,'' U.S. Trade
Representative Charlene Barshefsky told a farm group Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would end 20 years of annual congressional votes on
China's trade status and grant Beijing the same permanent
low-tariff access to U.S. markets that nearly every other nation in
the world already enjoys.
</P>
<P>
   It would also ease China's entry into the World Trade
Organization, the Geneva-based organization that oversees world
trade.
</P>
<P>
   The House panel added bipartisan language to the legislation
designed to protect U.S. industries from surges in certain exports
from China. It would allow the president to grant financial relief
to industries battered by such surges.
</P>
<P>
   Separate legislation to set up a commission to monitor human
rights in China was also expected to be included once the bill gets
to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer, D-Texas, called
the legislation ''a win-win for the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure drew only four negative votes on the House panel,
all Democratic: Reps. Fortney Pete Stark, D-Calif.; William J.
Coyne, D-Pa.; John Lewis, D-Ga; and Gerald D. Kleczka, D-Wis.
</P>
<P>
   At least six committee members -- five of them Democrats -- who
had previously been undecided voted for the bill: Reps. Mac
Collins, R-Ga.; Benjamin Cardin, D-Md.; Karen L. Thurman, D-Fla.;
Lloyd Doggett, D-Texas; William Jefferson, D-La.; and Richard Neal,
D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The China trade bills are H.R. 4444 and S. 2277
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House working group on China:
http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO campaign to stop China trade bill:
http://www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
