<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 06:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Debates How To Fight AIDS  </HEADLINE>
By GEIR MOULSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- World Health Organization members are debating how
to move forward in tackling the AIDS epidemic, with Brazil urging
the U.N. health agency to set up a global database of drug prices.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting Wednesday of WHO's annual assembly, Brazilian
Health Minister Jose Serra proposed that WHO ''establish a
computerized database in order to provide member states with
information on prices of essential drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   The call was backed by Uganda, Mexico and South Africa among
others, but received a cool initial response from WHO. Adviser
Michael Schultz said that maintaining a ''comprehensive and
reliable database on prices,'' rather than monitoring prices
locally, could strain the agency's resources.
</P>
<P>
   ''Prices change every week and to survey this on a worldwide
basis seems to be a humongous task for which WHO certainly today is
not equipped at all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, five pharmaceutical companies -- Britain's Glaxo
Wellcome, Germany's Boehringer Ingelheim, Roche of Switzerland, and
Bristol-Myers Squibb and Merck and Co. of the United States --
announced a commitment to reduce the cost of medicines for
governments and agencies in developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   Health workers have regularly complained that the cost of
patented AIDS drugs is so high that people in developing countries
are effectively blocked from receiving the care they need.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil and South Africa were among countries that backed the
local production of drugs to cut prices. A final decision on the
WHO resolution is expected later this week.
</P>
<P>
   The medical aid group Doctors Without Borders strongly backed
Brazil's database proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ''The WHO and countries are here to ensure that the public
health of populations takes priority over private profit,'' Ellen
't Hoen of Doctors Without Borders said. ''Member states need
information and choice to ensure the best health care for their
people,'' including information on cheaper generic drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe made its own call for WHO ''to determine the best price
that could be obtained for a treatment regime for HIV/AIDS of
acceptable quality.''
</P>
<P>
   A committee of the WHO assembly is to meet again Friday to
discuss planned amendments to a resolution on HIV/AIDS, including
Brazil's, officials said today.
</P>
<P>
   That resolution should provide a ''booster to enhance the
attention and the resources that are directed to the overall
response to HIV/AIDS,'' senior WHO policy adviser Daniel Tarantola
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Tarantola said the agreement could help clear the way to deal
with other problems, such as weak health services and uneven
distribution systems.
</P>
<P>
   ''The high cost of drugs has in some cases been the tree that
was hiding the forest,'' he said. ''No one was really going beyond
that tree because the obstacle appeared to be so insurmountable.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 70 percent of the world's 33.6 million HIV-infected
people live in sub-Saharan Africa, where governments do not have
the resources to subsidize the medicine to an affordable level.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's announcement brought a cautious welcome from some
governments and aid groups, who said they wanted to see more
details.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to qualify this with a lot of caution'' ahead of talks
with the companies involved, Tarantola said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-18-00 0656 </TRAILER>
