<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 08:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clint Eastwood, Disabled Spar  </HEADLINE>
By JANELLE CARTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Actor Clint Eastwood is getting his day, if
not making it, in a battle with advocates for the disabled who say
his California hotel is in violation of the Americans With
Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   A California woman has sued the actor, prompting an outcry from
Eastwood about what he says are frivolous lawsuits under the law
that target small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood, angered by a request from the woman for more than
$500,000 in attorneys fees, planned to ask a House subcommittee
today to amend the 10-year-old law so businesses like his Mission
Ranch Hotel in Carmel, Calif., have more time to comply.
</P>
<P>
   A bill sponsored by Florida Republicans Mark Foley and Clay Shaw
would require plaintiffs to give defendants notice of alleged
violations and then 90 days to comply.
</P>
<P>
   ''I totally support the ADA laws. I think people not in
compliance should get into compliance,'' Eastwood said in a
telephone interview Wednesday. But he added, ''I think there should
be a better way to get people in compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Foley, ''I don't want to create an impediment to the ADA.
In fairness, businesses should be given a chance to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   The case against Eastwood, filed three years ago, claims the
former Carmel mayor violated ADA provisions in his 32-room Mission
Ranch Hotel and restaurant. At least one bathroom and the hotel
parking lot did not comply with the law and there were not enough
rooms accessible to the disabled, the suit claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Rein, who represented plaintiff Diane Zum Brunnen in the
suit, said Eastwood's fight for notification is unfair to the
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ''If a black person is not allowed to enter a business because
of his race, he's not required to send a letter. If a woman is not
allowed to ..., she's not required to send a letter. Why should
disabled persons be the only class of persons required to send
letters?'' Rein said.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood insists his hotel is in compliance and says he and
other small businesses are being preyed upon by money-seeking
attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit demands $577,000 in attorneys fees. The disabled
cannot collect monetary damages under the law, although Rein says
the lawsuit does demand $25,000 for Brunnen under a California
statute.
</P>
<P>
   ''He thinks I'm some stiff coming along that's going to roll
over,'' Eastwood said. ''I'm going to trial. I'm going to take it
before a judge and a jury.''
</P>
<P>
   The actor said he is fighting for other small business owners as
well. ''A lot of people can't afford that. Somebody has got to
stand up for those people. Somebody has got to help out.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocate for the disabled fear the fight could result in
weakening the law once lawmakers begin reviewing it.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once we open up this bill, there's no way to control the
number of amendments that may come forward,'' said Curt Decker,
executive director of the National Association of Protection and
Advocacy Systems. ''This is going to be a message to anybody that
has not complied... Despite a decade of legal requirements
nationally, they are basically being given a free ride for not
complying with the law.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 3590
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-18-00 0841 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000518.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 08:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 13-year-old boy accused of stabbing woman more than 60 times, killing her </HEADLINE>
By TINA MOORE
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORRISVILLE, Pa. (AP) -- An autopsy shows that a woman killed in
her home -- allegedly by her 13-year-old neighbor -- was stabbed more
than 60 times, the district attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's scary, real scary,'' said Koupa Samuels, 25, who lives in
an apartment complex next to the house where Darlyne Jules, 33, was
killed. ''I know I'm going to be looking for somewhere else soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Jules' neighbor, Kareem Watts, was charged with murder and was
being held in a juvenile detention center without bail. He could
serve life in prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Bucks County District Attorney Diane Gibbons said she knew of no
motive.
</P>
<P>
   ''I asked him if he understood. He just shook his head,'' said
District Justice Joanne V. Kline, adding that Watts showed no
emotion during a preliminary hearing early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The victim's 7-year-old son, Alan Lubin, told police he saw
Watts sitting on top of his mother, who was lying on the sofa, and
stabbing her in the chest. Alan ran upstairs to his mother's
bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, he and his younger brother found their mother
dead and ran to a neighbor's house.
</P>
<P>
   Watts lived near the victim, about 300 feet from his own
apartment and past a dilapidated playground and a few yards down a
tree-lined street.
</P>
<P>
   Jules, a native of Haiti, rented a white, Cape Cod-style home,
which was backed by a supermarket parking lot and the playground.
Morrisville is located across the Delaware River from Trenton.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Watts stabbed Jules in the head, face, neck, chest,
torso and arm, spattering blood around the room leaving her body
under a pile of clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Her son told police that Watts entered the home Monday night
saying he needed to use the telephone. Later, Alan told authorities
he heard his mother screaming for someone to call police.
</P>
<P>
   Alan went downstairs and saw his mom lying on the couch with
Watts on top of her. He told police Watts had a knife in his hand
and was stabbing Jules in the chest while she screamed.
</P>
<P>
   Alan ran back upstairs, calling to his mother but Watts
answered, saying that he was helping Jules with some clothing. In
the morning, the 7-year-old went back downstairs and found his
lifeless mother lying under a pile of clothes, and then ran for
help.
</P>
<P>
   Alan's younger brother and his newborn baby sister were also in
the house all night Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Watts' mother, Janice, told police she left their apartment
several times during the night to purchase crack cocaine and that
she had also gone looking for her son, who was upset.
</P>
<P>
   ''He didn't do it,'' Janice Watts told WCAU-TV. ''I know he
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Court papers showed Janice Watts had pleaded guilty to a charge
of possession of crack cocaine in 1998. In the two years since
then, she had violated her probation at least once by using drugs,
according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   Kareem Watts had been on probation until recently after pleading
''non-adversarial'' -- a juvenile court term equivalent to a guilty
plea -- two years ago to charges of simple assault and possession of
a weapon on school grounds, Bucks County Juvenile Court official
Bill Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said Watts, then 11, brought an air rifle or paintball gun
to a school and was involved in an altercation. He was placed in a
supervision program, which he completed successfully, Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Henry Watts, 39, is serving time in a Delaware
prison on robbery charges, and had a 1992 robbery conviction in
Bucks County.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors who knew Jules, who was an unemployed amateur artist,
said she was a kind woman who loved her children.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was very nice, friendly, devoted to her kids,'' said Lee
Ann McClease, 26, who was pregnant at the same time as Jules. The
two women talked about having babies; Jules had had her newborn
just over a week before she was killed.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was too trusting and too friendly,'' said neighbor Mary
Singleton, 46.
</P>
<P>
   The Americana Terrace Apartments where Watts lived consists of
several two-story brick bunkers and fronts a stretch of road that
neighbors call ''apartment row.''
</P>
<P>
   Police were looking for the murder weapon on Wednesday. Officers
pulled on plastic gloves before they stepped inside the house,
which was surrounded with yellow crime-scene tape.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbons said all three of Jules' children were doing fine. The
boys were staying with their father, whom officials identified as
John Lubin, a Willingboro, N.J., truck driver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
