<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Open Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices were higher in early trading
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 22 points in the early
going. Advancing issues on the New York Stock Exchange held a 6-5
lead over decliners.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq Composite Index was ahead 12 points and the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 Stock Index was up 3.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street opened in somewhat of a news vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   The only economic news is the latest weekly jobless claims
figure, and there aren't any headline-grabbing earnings reports to
study.
</P>
<P>
   One story of interest is a Wall Street Journal article about
regulatory concerns over WorldCom's purchase of Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   In overseas trading, Tokyo share prices were sharply lower on
the heels of Wednesday's Wall Street weakness.
</P>
<P>
   However, stocks turned mostly higher in Europe. And bond prices
are fairly steady.
</P>
