<HEADLINE> Dow Rises 65; Nasdaq Down 15  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in early trading today as
investors sought direction in a market facing rising interest rates
and a dearth of significant economic news.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 65.46 at 10,835.20.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Nasdaq composite index
was down 14.70 at 3,630.26, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
up 4.04 at 1,451.84.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint fell 2 3/16 to 55 13/16. The Wall Street Journal reported
today that federal antitrust enforcers have recommended blocking
WorldCom Inc.'s $115 billion buyout of Sprint because it would
violate antitrust law. WorldCom shares fell 1\ to 40}.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos rose 7 17/64 to 64~. After the close of trading Wednesday,
the company reported better-than-expected results for its fiscal
third quarter. Analysts said investors were pleased with the
earnings report, but remain wary of the stock due to concerns about
the proposed takeover of Lycos by Spain's Terra Networks SA.
</P>
<P>
   The broader market was fairly quiet as investors continued to
scout a new path in a market facing higher interest rates. The
Federal Reserve raised interest rates for the sixth time since June
on Tuesday, pushing the federal funds rate -- the interest that
banks charge each other -- to 6.5 percent, the highest level in nine
years.
</P>
<P>
   Escalating borrowing costs make it tougher to borrow money to
finance growth. Ultimately, that can cut into corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 111.14 million
shares, compared with 115.57 million at the same time Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 0.91 to 498.75.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 2.1 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.1 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.8 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
