<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suspect arrested in vandalism of church statues in Brooklyn  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A man who police say confessed to participating
in a series of vandalism attacks on Roman Catholic statues in
Brooklyn told investigators he was following orders from God,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He told us that he believed that God had told him to do it --
that the Bible suggested to him that he should not worship graven
images,'' Police Commissioner Howard Safir said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Primus St. Croix allegedly led a group of less than a dozen
followers, but has named only two who allegedly helped him damage
statues of the Virgin Mary, saints and other religious figures,
said Deputy Inspector Barbara Sicilia, head of the NYPD's Hate
Crime Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   Police said St. Croix, 34, confessed to participating in five of
the 11 vandalism incidents but he and his followers are believed to
be responsible for the bulk of them. St. Croix confessed to
vandalizing three churches, a Knights of Columbus hall and a
convent.
</P>
<P>
   St. Croix, an illegal alien from St. Lucia, was arrested Tuesday
night near his apartment in Manhattan's Morningside Heights section
after a tip was called in to the NYPD's Crime Stoppers, Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect was arraigned early today in Brooklyn on charges
including second-degree criminal mischief, a felony punishable by
up to 2{ years in prison. He was ordered held on $100,000 bail, and
is due back in court on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   St. Croix told police he was baptized Catholic but does not
practice the religion, Sicilia said.
</P>
<P>
   While police interviewed the suspect, he quoted often from the
Bible, and Sicilia said several verses stood out when St. Croix
discussed Deuteronomy, Chapter 12, verses one through five.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that passage reads: ''Break down their altars, smash
their sacred stones ... cut down the idols of their gods and wipe
out their names from those places. You must not worship the Lord
your God in their way.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Croix admitted to vandalizing statues in the incidents where
the figures' hands or heads had been cut off, Sicilia said. Other
statues were marred without any parts being removed.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's showing by destroying them, he's showing people that it's
only material, it's stone, it's broken, there's nothing spiritual
here,'' Sicilia explained.
</P>
<P>
   The places vandalized were apparently chosen at random -- most
are near where St. Croix used to live in Brooklyn. A self-employed
day laborer who works in the demolition and construction field, St.
Croix moved to Manhattan about a month ago to live with his
girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   He told police he sought out statues early Sunday mornings
because he knew the damage would affect people going to church,
Sicilia said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He would get up, feel this message to do it, and whatever
church came across his path, was the one,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   St. Croix said he used a sledgehammer, and police were looking
for it.
</P>
<P>
   Frank DeRosa, spokesman for the Diocese of Brooklyn, said
parishioners are encouraged that there's been an arrest in some of
the incidents, but saddened at the reason for the destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ''The statues of Jesus, or of the Blessed Mother or the saints
are there to remind us how to live the Christian life -- there is no
idolatry involved,'' DeRosa said.
</P>
<P>
   The vandalism began last Sept. 26 at St. Jerome's Roman Catholic
Church in Flatbush where a statue of the Virgin Mary was knocked to
the ground, its face and hands destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   The next desecration was on Oct. 24 at Our Lady of Refuge Church
in Flatbush. A statue of the Virgin Mary holding baby Jesus was
knocked down, its head missing.
</P>
<P>
   Then in January, the vandals struck three churches, a convent
and a private residence over two days. Police said St. Croix
confessed to the January incidents.
</P>
<P>
   In others, a sculpture of Pope Pius X was dragged away and
smashed, a Jesus statue was toppled, and religious objects at four
other churches, a monastery, and a private home were damaged.
</P>
<P>
   St. Croix faces five counts of second-degree criminal mischief,
five counts of third-degree criminal mischief and five counts of
first-degree aggravated harassment. The top count of second-degree
criminal mischief carries up to seven years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Diocese of Brooklyn: http://www.dioceseofbrooklyn.org.
</P>
<P>
   NYPD: http://www.ci.nyc.ny.us/html/nypd.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
