<HEADLINE> Conservative Party boss says looks like Giuliani running  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The head of the state Conservative Party
says ''it looks more and more'' as if Mayor Rudolph Giuliani will
continue in the U.S. Senate race against Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The politically savvy Michael Long said Wednesday he was not
basing his opinion on personal conversations with the mayor -- they
have been at political odds -- but on developments over the past
several days and his conversations with other politicians,
including Republican leaders from across the state.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, Giuliani said he still had not chosen a treatment
for his prostate cancer, a decision he has said will help him
determine if he can stay in the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't anticipate that I'll be in a position to make that
decision today,'' Giuliani said at a news conference. He said
choosing a cancer treatment has been ''a much more difficult
decision than I thought it would be,'' adding that ''I'm not
leaning'' toward any particular treatment at this point.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Bruce Teitelbaum, the mayor's campaign manager,
did confirm that Brendan Quinn, a former top aide to state GOP
Chairman William Powers who is now working for the Giuliani
campaign, had been dispatched to Buffalo to begin preparations for
the Republican state convention that will be held there May 30.
That convention is to nominate a Senate candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ''People shouldn't draw any inference from that except that the
campaign is moving forward,'' Teitelbaum said. ''The convention is
in two weeks and we have to be prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   In another indication that Giuliani has not scrapped plans for a
Senate run, several Republican leaders from across the state have
been invited to join him at a televised town hall forum in
Manhattan tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel committed to do it and I will do it,'' Giuliani said
this morning, referring to the evening forum.
</P>
<P>
   The estrangement between Long and Giuliani, over the mayor's
continued support of abortion rights and his closeness with Liberal
Party boss Raymond Harding, was in evidence Wednesday night as the
Conservative Party held its annual fund-raising dinner at a
Manhattan hotel.
</P>
<P>
   No Republican has won statewide office in New York since 1974
without Conservative Party backing and the mayor was not even
invited to the dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's never been endorsed by the Conservative Party,'' Long
explained. ''He goes to the Liberal Party's dinners.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani camp is fond of pointing out that no Democrat has
been elected governor or U.S. senator in New York without Liberal
Party backing since the party was founded more than 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Among the featured speakers at the Wednesday night dinner were
Republican Gov. George Pataki, who while a backer of Giuliani's
Senate bid has had chilly relations with the mayor. Also on the
dinner's dais, but not speaking, was former Rep. Joseph DioGuardi,
the Westchester County Republican who is seeking Conservative Party
backing with Long's blessing for a Senate run.
</P>
<P>
   That means Pataki could be helping to raise money for a party
that could then spend it against Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's going to the dinner because he's a friend of Mike Long
and because the Conservative Party supports him,'' Pataki
spokeswoman Zenia Mucha said before the governor's attendance at
the dinner.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to facing cancer, Giuliani is also going through
very public marital woes. On Friday night, just days after
announcing that he and his wife of 16 years, Donna Hanover, were
discussing a separation, the mayor took a very public stroll after
dinner with his self-described ''very good friend,'' Judith Nathan.
</P>
<P>
   Long said that while he thought the mayor would continue to run
for Senate, he also felt ''more and more Republicans want him out''
of the race.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the perfect scenario for Mike Long and the Conservative
Party,'' Long said. ''The Quinnipiac poll showed us at this moment
at 5 percent and that's without a campaign yet and without anybody
knowing'' our candidate. ''Some of my own leaders don't know who's
running.''
</P>
<P>
   A poll Tuesday from the Quinnipiac College Polling Institute had
Clinton at 42 percent, Giuliani at 41 percent and DioGuardi at 5
percent among New York's registered voters asked about a possible
three-way race.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, DioGuardi announced that he had sent letters to
Pataki and all members of the Republican state committee asking
them to get behind his candidacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-18-00 1159 </TRAILER>
