<HEADLINE> Truck, Bus Rest Rules Hearings Set  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Transportation Department will hold a
series of seven hearings around the country seeking comments on its
plan to change the rules setting the hours truck and bus drivers
can work.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, drivers would have to rest longer between
shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the goal is to reduce the number of accidents
caused by exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   The government wants to set limits for five different classes of
drivers, with long-distance operators limited to no more than 12
hours of driving in a 24-hour period. They would also have to
install electronic monitors on their vehicles to track their work
hours.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing schedule is:
</P>
<P>
   --May 31 and June 1: Department of Transportation, Washington.
</P>
<P>
   --June 7-8: Ontario Convention Center, Ontario, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   --June 12-13: Jefferson County Fairgrounds, Auditorium 2, Golden,
Colo.
</P>
<P>
   --June 15-16: Wagstaff Theater, Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   --June 20-21: Indiana State Fairgrounds, Union Federal Southwest
Pavilion, Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   --June 26-27: Quality Inn Conference Center, 51 Hartford
Turnpike, Vernon, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   --June 29-30: Meeting Room, Atlanta South Truck Stop, Jackson,
Ga.
</P>
</TEXT>
