<DOCNO> APW20000518.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Specter Advocates Embryo Research  </HEADLINE>
By CLAUDE R. MARX
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A cure for Lou Gehrig's disease -- a fatal
malady that robs its victims of the ability to control even basic
movements such as swallowing -- might be found faster if only
Congress would allow research using human embryos, Sen. Arlen
Specter said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Specter, R-Pa., long a supporter of stem cell research, once
again waded into the mire of embryo research as witnesses before a
Senate panel asked for more federal funding to find a cure for the
disease, also known as Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis, or ALS.
</P>
<P>
   ''I cry at the thought of not being able to tell my husband and
daughter that I love them, and I weep at the thought of my father
burying another child,'' 32-year-old victim Shelbie Oppenheimer of
New Hope, Pa., told the Senate Appropriations subcommittee on
labor, health and human services and education, the panel that
controls funding of health research.
</P>
<P>
   ALS attacks nerve cells in the brain and spinal cord. Stem cells
are the basic or primordial cells from which all human tissues and
organs develop. By themselves, the cells can't grow into a person.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has not funded any research into
embryonic stem cells because of a 1996 congressional ban on any
research that destroys human embryos -- and taking stem cells from
embryos does destroy them.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Specter praised a decision by the National Institutes
of Health to fund experiments using lab-grown stem cells derived
from aborted fetuses and from unused embryos from infertility
treatments. His stand was decried by some anti-abortion groups that
call stem cell research morally unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   The NIH will spend $20 million this year to find a cure for ALS,
which is often called Lou Gehrig's disease in honor of the New York
Yankee first baseman who died of it in 1941. Funding for ALS
research has been steadily increasing over the years. NIH's total
budget is $2.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gerald Fischbach, the government's lead researcher on brain
diseases, said researchers feel a ''cautious optimism that stopping
ALS and other neurological disorders is a realistic goal.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he said, ''the problems ALS presents are complex and
medical progress is notoriously difficult to predict.''
</P>
<P>
   Fischbach, director of NIH's National Institute of Neurological
Disorders and Stroke, said he believes embryonic stem cells could
be helpful in developing a cure because they could create neurons
to replace those destroyed by ALS.
</P>
<P>
   Television actor Blair Underwood also urged more funding. ''We
are on the threshold of great progress in the treatment of ALS,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Underwood, the star of the CBS show ''City of Angels,'' said he
a was a caregiver to his maternal grandmother, who died of ALS in
1978.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lois Capps, D-Calif., urged passage of legislation that
would waive the 24-month waiting period for Medicare coverage for
ALS patients.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: National Institute of Neurological Disorders and
Stroke: http://www.ninds.nih.gov
</P>
<P>
   ALS Association: http://www.ALSA.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-18-00 1424 </TRAILER>
