<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greenspan Backs China Trade Bill  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With just a week to go, both sides of the
China trade debate ratcheted up their lobbying campaigns Thursday,
with supporters drawing within striking distance of a win in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents posed outside the Capitol with a 200-foot metal chain
to dramatize the plight of China's political prisoners. In a
competing event, President Clinton gave Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan
a Rose Garden podium to pitch the landmark legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The vote ''will have profound implications for the free world's
trading system and the long-term growth potential of the American
economy,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also planned a five-minute Oval Office speech to the
nation Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would extend permanent normal trade relations to China
and ease the way for its entry into the 135-nation World Trade
Organization. It would end two decades of annual congressional
votes on China's trade status.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters remained publicly cautious, saying they still lack
the 218 affirmative votes needed for House passage. ''We are not
where we need to be. We have more votes to get,'' said White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   But, privately, other administration officials and their
congressional allies were far more optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   The House takes up the legislation next week, with a final vote
expected Wednesday or Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Although widely supported in the Senate, most House Democrats
remain opposed, due in large part to a fierce lobbying campaign by
organized labor. Business groups have rallied in support of the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides staged increasingly elaborate rallies and news
conferences Thursday to vie for the dwindling band of undecideds.
</P>
<P>
   House Democratic Whip David Bonior of Michigan, the chief
opponent, and four other House opponents joined about 60 exiled
Chinese human rights activists in hoisting the 200-foot chain
outside the Capitol. They said it represented imprisoned human
rights, religious and labor leaders in China.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ask them and what they'll tell you is that while this trade
deal may lift tariffs, it won't pry open the door to a single
prison cell,'' Bonior said.
</P>
<P>
   The activists erected a display listing the names of victims of
the bloody 1989 Tiananmen Square crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should not take all of the pressure and leverage off of
China...,'' said House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., an
opponent. ''When we give China the Good Housekeeping seal of
approval, things get really bad for the forces for democracy and
the dissident voices in that country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonior says as many as two-thirds of the 211 House Democrats
will oppose the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters concede that's a possibility. But Rep. Robert Matsui,
D-Calif., a top Democratic supporter, said he still expects to be
able to deliver 70-80 Democratic votes. If 140-150 Republicans vote
for the measure, as is expected, that puts supporters close to or
just over the needed majority.
</P>
<P>
   Some supporters said they expected even more than 150 GOP votes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Matsui said. ''It's going to take a little time yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two days, the bill has picked up the support of at
least 10 previously undeclared Democrats and a like number of
previously undeclared Republicans. More were expected before the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan endorsed the bill last week, but the White House had
the Fed chairman do it again.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all know when Chairman Greenspan talks, the world
listens,'' Clinton said. ''I just hope the Congress is listening
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that China accounts for about 3 percent of world trade,
Greenspan said U.S. markets ''are already generally open to China''
and would not be affected by passage of the so-called permanent
normal trade relations bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''Passage of PNTR, however, will facilitate a further opening of
China's markets to U.S. producers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Clinton would continue to make his case in
one-on-one sessions with undecided House members. Sunday's 7 p.m.
EDT address was partly in response to appeals from congressional
supporters that he do so, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bills are H.R. 4444 and S. 2277.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House working group on China:
http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO campaign to stop China trade bill:
http://www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
