<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani set to appear at town hall meeting  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Three weeks after he told the world he had
prostate cancer and might not continue his run for the U.S. Senate,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani appears to be leaning toward staying in the
race against Democrat Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   New York Republican leaders were invited to join the mayor at a
nationally televised town hall forum Thursday night in Manhattan
and a Giuliani campaign aide was sent to Buffalo to prepare for the
state GOP convention, which will nominate a Senate candidate in two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Giuliani insisted Thursday that he has not yet chosen a
cancer treatment -- a step which he said will precede any
announcement of whether he will keep up the run for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have not made a decision. ... I don't believe I'll make a
decision today,'' Giuliani said at a morning news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''The medical decision is a much more difficult decision than I
thought it would be,'' said the former federal prosecutor. ''I
thought it would be like a budget or a (court) case, but it is a
much more personal decision.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as the mayor was insisting that he had not made a
decision, his campaign manager, Bruce Teitelbaum, stood nearby
smiling -- a marked contrast to his gloomy outlook last week when it
appeared as if the mayor would pull out.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's three options for treatment are surgery, external
beam radiation and radioactive seed implantation. The 15-year
survival rate is 95 percent for surgery and 60 to 70 percent for
the two less invasive options.
</P>
<P>
   Teitelbaum confirmed Wednesday that Brendan Quinn, a former top
aide to state GOP Chairman William Powers who is now working for
the Giuliani campaign, is in Buffalo beginning preparations for the
May 30 Republican state convention.
</P>
<P>
   In a further indication that Giuliani had not scrapped plans for
a Senate run, Republican leaders from across the state were invited
to his town hall-style meeting on the Upper East Side.
</P>
<P>
   The past three weeks have been particularly rocky for the mayor:
He disclosed that he has cancer; announced he is seeking a legal
separation from hiw wife, Donna Hanover; confirmed his relationship
with Judith Nathan, a woman whom he has called a ''very good
friend''; and denied his wife's suggestion that he earlier had an
affair with one of his aides.
</P>
</TEXT>
