<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mental Health Benefit Laws Skirted  </HEADLINE>
By ALICE ANN LOVE
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fourteen percent of employers surveyed by
government auditors are not complying with a law requiring that
they offer the same dollar amount of health insurance coverage for
mental illness as they do for physical illness, a report released
Thursday found.
</P>
<P>
   Many others are placing alternative restrictions on benefits
that skirt the Mental Health Parity Act, which took effect in 1998,
according to the report by the General Accounting Office.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because of ... reductions in mental health benefits that the
employers have made to offset the required enhancements, compliance
may have little effect on employees' access to mental health
services,'' said auditors from the GAO, the investigative arm of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers are considering whether to make the mental health
parity law stricter. Without congressional action, it will expire
Sept. 30, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The matter was discussed Thursday at a hearing of the Senate
Health, Education and Workforce Committee. The committee chairman,
Sen. James Jeffords, R-Vt., said lawmakers have ''demonstrated a
clear interest in increasing access to quality mental health care
for all Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   The law does not require companies to offer mental health
coverage as part of employee health benefits. But if they do, the
maximum annual and lifetime dollar amount of benefits available
must be the same as for physical health coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The law allows other restrictions on mental health services to
differ from physical health coverage, such as copayments or limits
on the number of visits allowed per year.
</P>
<P>
   GAO auditors surveyed employers in 26 states and the District of
Columbia to determine their compliance. They found 14 percent of
companies were not abiding by the parity requirement for total
dollar amounts of coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Of the majority in compliance, 87 percent have other coverage
rules that are more restrictive for mental health. Many have added
those restrictions recently.
</P>
<P>
   ''While there may be adherence to the letter of the law, there
are violations of the spirit of the law,'' said Sen. Pete Domenici,
R-N.M., who has introduced legislation with Sen. Paul Wellstone,
D-Minn., to close the loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   Employers and insurance companies warn against that.
</P>
<P>
   ''Extending full parity in this area will drive up the costs of
coverage and increase the number of uninsured Americans,'' said
Dean Rosen, testifying for the Health Insurance Association of
America.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO said compliance with the existing federal law has
increased insurance claims costs by less than 1 percent in most
cases. In some states where mental health parity laws are more
comprehensive, cost increases have been 2 percent to 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The law does not apply to substance abuse treatment, group
health insurance at companies with fewer than 50 employees, or to
individual insurance policies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-18-00 1507 </TRAILER>
