<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fox 'Remakes' Fall Schedule  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- ''The X-Files'' returns with David Duchovny's
agent Mulder a part-timer next season, lending Fox some stability
as it announced the most extensive remake of any of the broadcast
networks Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Titanic'' producer James Cameron, ''Ally McBeal'' creator
David E. Kelley, ''The X-Files'' creator Chris Carter and ''ER''
creator Michael Crichton are some of the big names behind Fox's
nine new series.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, UPN is adding three new series and picking up ''The
Hughleys'' after it was canceled by ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has slumped badly this year and faced further uncertainty
with the retirement of its long-running shows ''Beverly Hills
90210'' and ''Party of Five.'' It couldn't afford to lose its
biggest drama, ''The X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   The network reached separate deals with Carter and Duchovny this
week to continue. Co-star Gillian Anderson was already contracted
for another year. Duchovny's deal, completed Wednesday, calls for
him to film 11 episodes, or half the 22 new episodes that most
series film each year.
</P>
<P>
   That enabled Fox to keep intact its Sunday schedule, its most
successful night of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Fox will also carry ''The Lone Gunmen,'' a spinoff of ''The
X-Files'' that Carter is creating, on its Thursday schedule next
season. It will be paired with a Crichton-created drama that does
not even have a title or cast yet. Fox is giving Carter and
Crichton extra time, and won't debut the Thursday schedule until
the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Mondays are being turned over entirely to Kelley. His new
series, ''Boston Public,'' follows a group of teachers working at a
high school in suburban Boston. It will be followed by ''Ally
McBeal,'' his returning series about a group of lawyers working at
a firm in downtown Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron is producing ''Dark Angel,'' a science-fiction adventure
series set in ''post-apocalyptic America.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox returns two comedies whose midseason successes were among
the network's only bright spots this year, ''Malcolm in the
Middle'' and ''Titus.'' One new comedy is ''Don't Ask,'' which
stars John Goodman as a gay dad.
</P>
<P>
   Absent from Fox's schedule is the game show ''Greed,'' which was
quickly put together to capitalize on the success of ''Who Wants to
Be a Millionaire.'' Fox has also canceled ''Time of Your Life,''
''Get Real'' and ''Family Guy.''
</P>
<P>
   UPN recovered from a near-death experience this year to surge
past its archrival, the WB, in the ratings. It was almost entirely
because of its new Thursday night World Wrestling Federation
franchise, which will return.
</P>
<P>
   The network adds two new series on Friday nights: ''Freedom,''
an action series made by ''Matrix'' producer Joel Silver, and
''Level 9,'' a drama about an FBI unit trained to hunt down
high-tech criminals. Both series are trying to grab the young, male
audience that is UPN's target.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are proud to be known as the guy network,'' said UPN chief
executive Dean Valentine. ''Somebody needs to stand up for the
high-testosterone American male.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting in February, UPN said it will broadcast games of the
new XFL football league created by the World Wrestling Federation.
NBC is broadcasting XFL games on Saturday nights. UPN also plans to
produce a weekly rap music countdown series with the hip-hop
magazine The Source.
</P>
<P>
   UPN is canceling ''Dilbert,'' ''The Beat,'' ''Malcolm &AMP; Eddie,''
''The Grown-Ups'' and ''I Dare You.''
</P>
<P>
   Continuing its wrestling theme, UPN said it will hold the first
wrestling awards show next year, the Slammys. Wrestlers will
compete in categories such as ''best hair.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-18-00 1513 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000518.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eastwood Wants Disabled Law Changed  </HEADLINE>
By JANELLE CARTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Angered by a lawsuit against his own hotel,
actor Clint Eastwood urged Congress on Thursday to amend the
Americans with Disabilities Act and discourage what he calls
frivolous lawsuits by attorneys reaping six-figure legal fees from
small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really not fair,'' Eastwood told lawmakers in a House
judiciary subcommittee hearing. ''These lawyers cloak themselves
under the guise they're doing a favor for the disabled when really
they're doing a disservice.''
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood has been speaking out since a California woman sued him
and cited his Mission Ranch Hotel in Carmel, Calif. for violations
to the 10-year-old law.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed three years ago, claims at least one bathroom
and the hotel parking lot at the 32-room hotel and restaurant did
not comply with the law and there were not enough rooms accessible
to the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood says the claims are bogus. An accessible bathroom, for
instance, has been in place since 1988, he insists.
</P>
<P>
   The actor has lashed out at provisions in the federal law that
prohibit the disabled from collecting damages but allow attorneys
to collect fees. Paul Rein, the attorney for plaintiff Diane Zum
Brunnen, is asking for $577,000 in legal fees, Eastwood said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers drive off ''in a big Mercedes and the disabled end
up riding off in a wheelchair,'' Eastwood said.
</P>
<P>
   A bill sponsored by Florida Republican Reps. Mark Foley and Clay
Shaw would require plaintiffs to give defendants notice of alleged
violations and then 90 days to comply.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ADA is being used by some attorneys to shake down
thousands of businesses from Florida to California,'' Foley told
the subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   He said the problem is especially perverse in Florida, where two
attorneys have filed a barrage of lawsuits against businesses,
including one by a disabled child unable to gain access to a liquor
store that the child would not have attempted to enter anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ''I call it legal extortion,'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democratic committee members seemed in a quandary over the
situation. ''It is a very difficult issue to deal with,'' said Rep.
Mel Watt, D-N.C., who added that in 22 years of practicing law, he
never filed a lawsuit without serving a defendant with notice.
</P>
<P>
   Rein, the attorney in the Eastwood case, said it would be unfair
to require the disabled to notify people they believe discriminated
against them.
</P>
<P>
   ''If a black person is not allowed to enter a business because
of his race, he's not required to send a letter. If a woman is not
allowed to ..., she's not required to send a letter. Why should
disabled persons be the only class of persons required to send
letters?'' Rein said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration also opposes the measure, saying in a
Justice Department letter to the subcommittee, ''We believe that
this proposed legislation would work to undermine voluntary
compliance ... and it would unduly burden legitimate ADA
enforcement activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Several disabled groups, including the Paralyzed Veterans of
America and the National Council on Independent Living, are also
opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Others had a different view. Business owners Donna and David
Batelaan of Lakeworth, Fla., run a mobility equipment business.
They are both in wheelchairs, as are two of their employees and
their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Batelaan's said they were hit with a lawsuit by an
attorney in New Jersey who, without notice, cited them for not
painting lines in the parking lot and posting a sign on one
''handicapped'' spot.
</P>
<P>
   ''It cost us less than $100 to correct the infraction and $2,000
in attorneys' fees,'' Donna Batelaan told the committee. ''We are
intensely concerned about the results of the greed displayed by
these suits being filed.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.house.gov/judiciary/2.htm
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 3590
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-18-00 1514 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000518.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judges Probe Clinton Letter Release  </HEADLINE>
By PETE YOST
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal appeals court expressed serious
reservations Thursday about a ruling that President Clinton
committed a crime in releasing the private letters of presidential
accuser Kathleen Willey.
</P>
<P>
   But two of the three appeals judges questioned whether they
should take the highly unusual step of intervening in an ongoing
lawsuit to set aside the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   In oral arguments, the Clinton administration urged the appeals
panel to step into the case filed by a conservative group, Judicial
Watch, concerning the Clinton administration's alleged violation of
the Privacy Act by gathering hundreds of FBI background files of
former Reagan and Bush appointees.
</P>
<P>
   It is highly unusual for appeals courts to involve themselves in
cases before they are disposed of.
</P>
<P>
   In a March 29 ruling, U.S. District Judge Royce Lamberth, a
Reagan appointee, found the president had the requisite intent to
commit a criminal violation of the Privacy Act when he authorized
the release of Willey's letters in the midst of the 1998 criminal
investigation that led to Clinton's impeachment and acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides viewed the Willey correspondence with the
president as vital to undercutting her allegation that Clinton made
an unwanted sexual advance. Much of Willey's friendly
correspondence with Clinton came after the alleged 1993 encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Although the case began with the FBI files issue, Lamberth gave
Judicial Watch wide latitude to explore whether the White House
routinely gathered and released damaging information about its
political opponents, a decision that led to inclusion of the Willey
letters even though Willey is not a party to the suit.
</P>
<P>
   ''This White House and all White Houses'' and the Justice
Department for more than two decades have said that the type of
action Clinton took with the Willey letters is not a violation of
the Privacy Act, said Appeals Judge Harry Edwards, a Carter
appointee.
</P>
<P>
   ''How in heavens name can a trial court judge say'' there was
intent ''to commit a crime? The Department of Justice makes this
decision,'' said Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't start!'' Edwards snapped when Judicial Watch head Larry
Klayman tried to argue the point, saying Clinton's release of the
Willey letters is part of a ''pattern and practice'' of violating
the Privacy Act.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptical of Klayman's arguments, Appeals Judge David Tatel, a
Clinton appointee, said that by the conservative group's logic,
''any release of documents that you believe subject'' to the
Privacy Act ''would be per se evidence of criminal conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The plain language'' of the law suggests that the Privacy Act
does not cover the president and his top advisers, Tatel said.
</P>
<P>
   Seeming to support the idea that the Privacy Act does apply to
Clinton, Appeals Judge Douglas Ginsburg, a Reagan appointee,
pointed to the legislative history of the Privacy Act: It was
enacted in the wake of the Watergate abuses of the Nixon White
House.
</P>
<P>
   But Ginsburg and Edwards suggested Lamberth's ruling could be
dealt with on appeal when the lawsuit ends.
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg questioned what harm would be done to the White House
by letting the lower court decision stand for now.
</P>
<P>
   Tatel suggested a different possibility: A ''remand'' of the
issue by the appeals court to the district court so Lamberth could
reconsider his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''Certainly that would be sufficient,'' replied Justice
Department lawyer William Schultz, though Schultz emphasized that
Lamberth's finding should be tossed out.
</P>
<P>
   The White House contends Lamberth's ruling allows Judicial Watch
to delve into privileged discussions between Clinton and his White
House lawyers that led to the release of Willey's letters.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing the White House's case, Schultz predicted Lamberth's
decision will have far-reaching implications, but Edwards suggested
the Clinton administration is exaggerating any harm.
</P>
<P>
   ''You come here'' saying that ''Judge Lamberth ... says the
president is a crook'' but ''are you assuming'' Lamberth ''is so
dishonest'' that the judge will allow the conservative group to
conduct overly broad inquiries that will invade privileged
conversations inside the White House, Edwards asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it's speculative to say the White House is at
risk,'' Schultz replied. He said Lamberth is letting Judicial Watch
range far afield in its lawsuit. Beside the Willey letters, the
judge allowed Judicial Watch to delve into the Pentagon's release
of incorrect information that Linda Tripp put on a form filed at
the Pentagon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-18-00 1522 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000518.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 49; Nasdaq Down 57  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in quiet trading today as
investors sought direction in a market facing rising interest rates
and a dearth of significant economic news.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market is just marking time,'' said Alan Ackerman, senior
vice president at Fahnestock &AMP; Co. in New York. ''We have buyers
and sellers just waiting it out for the time being.''
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the Dow
Jones industrial average was up 49.35 at 10,819.09.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Nasdaq composite
index was down 57.37 at 3,587.59, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 4.16 at 1,443.64.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint fell 1} to 56\. The Wall Street Journal reported today
that federal antitrust enforcers have recommended blocking WorldCom
Inc.'s $115 billion buyout of Sprint because it would violate
antitrust law. WorldCom shares fell 1 31/32 to 40 1/32.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos rose 5 1/64 to 62|. After the close of trading Wednesday,
the company reported better-than-expected results for its fiscal
third quarter. Analysts said investors were pleased with the
earnings report, but remain wary of the stock due to concerns about
the proposed takeover of Lycos by Spain's Terra Networks SA.
</P>
<P>
   The broader market was fairly quiet as investors continued to
seek a new path in a market facing higher interest rates. The
Federal Reserve raised interest rates for the sixth time since June
on Tuesday, pushing the federal funds rate -- the interest that
banks charge each other -- to 6.5 percent, the highest level in nine
years.
</P>
<P>
   Escalating borrowing costs make it tougher to borrow money to
finance growth. Ultimately, that can cut into corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a lingering case of interest rate jitters,'' Ackerman
said. ''There are not many who believe the Fed is near the end of
its rate hikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, financial stocks, which are vulnerable to interest rate
fluctuations, were modestly higher today. J.P. Morgan rose 1 7/16
to 134 1/16 and American Express rose ~ to 51 13/16. Merrill Lynch
rose 1{ to 109{.
</P>
<P>
   ''People have said unilaterally that that they don't want to own
financial stocks while interest rates are moving higher,'' said
Donald Berdine, chief investment officer at PNC Advisors. ''As a
result, many of them are now very reasonably priced.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts noted that the market now faces a dry spell of major
economic reports, with little to indicate whether the long series
of rate increases are successfully slowing the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Labor Department's weekly jobless claims report
showed that new claims for unemployment benefits fell last week for
the second week in a row. That suggested that companies are still
scrambling to find workers, leaving themselves vulnerable to
pressure to bump up wages and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The next economic report with true potential to move markets is
due May 25, when the Commerce Department issues its preliminary
report on first-quarter gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-4 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 639.70 million
shares, compared with 654.12 million at the same time Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 2.79 to 496.87.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
