<HEADLINE> Prostate patient goes on vandalism spree against doctors  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAPE MAY COURT HOUSE, N.J. (AP) -- Angry at urologists who
refused to perform diagnostic procedures on him, a man went on a
three-county vandalism rampage, shattering windows and
spray-painting signs at the doctors' offices, police said.
</P>
<P>
   John Murphy, 64, of Toms River allegedly damaged a dozen
doctors' offices in a three-county area of southern New Jersey on
May 10. He was arrested Monday and charged with 10 counts of
criminal mischief; more charges may be added later as the
investigation continues, according to Sgt. Al Della Fave of the
state police.
</P>
<P>
   He was being held Thursday on $2,500 bail in the Cape May County
jail.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is pretty heavy retaliation,'' said police Detective Greg
Hopper in Dover Township, where six offices were damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, a retired telephone company employee, was linked to the
incidents when investigators learned that he had been a patient of
every doctor whose office was targeted.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Murphy -- who was denied a procedure that day -- went
from office to office, damaging buildings in Lakewood, Dover
Township, Stafford Township, Linwood, Somers Point, Marmora and
Cape May Court House.
</P>
<P>
   He broke windows and used spray paint to black out the names of
the urologists on exterior signs, police said. In Marmora, he
allegedly threw a hammer and bricks through a plate-glass door. In
Linwood and Somers Point, a hammer and rock were used to break
office windows, according to Somers Point police Detective Michael
Boyd.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every single one of these doctors had treated Mr. Murphy and
terminated him as a patient after he had insisted on unnecessary
and invasive medical procedures,'' Della Fave said.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't clear whether he was sick in any way or just wanted
the procedures done. He was given a psychological evaluation before
being jailed, Della Fave said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the victims was Dr. Shah Chaudhry of Somers Point, who
examined Murphy more than a year ago. Murphy stormed out of the
office after Chaudhry refused to perform a prostate biopsy,
Chaudhry said.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy had had one performed by another doctor. Chaudhry told
him to provide the results of the first one.
</P>
<P>
   ''The procedure is pretty invasive. You go through the rectum,''
Chaudhry said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Thomas Feneran, whose Stafford Township office had windows
broken and signs spray-painted, said repairs could top $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Feneran said Thursday he treated Murphy once, two years ago. He
wouldn't discuss the visit further, citing doctor-patient
confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had no idea there was anyone else who had this happen to
them until later, when I found out from other urologist friends of
mine. It was so similar, it would be difficult to believe that they
weren't related,'' Feneran said.
</P>
<P>
   State police said Murphy admitted to the vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said he was trying to put them out of business,'' said
Detective Karl Ulbrich. ''He wanted to get back at the doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy could not be reached for comment Thursday. A jail guard
refused to give him a telephone message, referring a reporter to
the public defender's office. Murphy is not represented by a public
defender, a man there said. There was no answer at Murphy's home,
where the telephone rang unanswered Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
