<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of U.S. Grizzlies Calculated  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- There are 332 grizzly bears in Glacier
National Park -- more or less -- according to scientists from the
U.S. Geological Survey.
</P>
<P>
   That's an increase from the 200 grizzlies estimated to be in the
park during the 1970s, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The new count is based on a study of bear DNA collected from the
animals hair and droppings.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say this gives a more accurate count than trying to
find all the bears individually. It's easier on the bears and the
scientists, too.
</P>
<P>
   Previous grizzly bear population studies in forested habitats
typically were accomplished with live capture, radio collars and
aerial tracking of bears, which is expensive and disruptive to
bears, as well as to park visitors.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the count for the park, the researchers estimated
there are 437 grizzlies in the northern one-third of the Northern
Continental Divide Ecosystem, which includes the park and stretches
from the Canadian border to near Missoula, Mont.
</P>
<P>
   Because of statistical variation, the actual numbers of bears in
the northern third of the NCDE may vary from 349 to 590 bears and
from 241 to 549 bears in Glacier National Park, said researcher
Katherine Kendall.
</P>
<P>
   While the new numbers are higher than the estimates of the
1970s, Kendall said the earlier numbers are thought to be
unreliable and thus people should not draw any conclusions about
population trends by comparing the two.
</P>
<P>
   Grizzly bears once roamed most of the North American continent,
but researchers estimate that fewer than 1,000 remain south of the
Canadian border today.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall reached the new numbers by identifying species, sex and
individual bears from DNA extracted from bear hair and scats -- bear
poop. The bears were lured to collecting areas where their hair was
caught on wire or was scraped off on trees they rubbed against. DNA
is the material contained in every living cell that provides a
blueprint for that individual organism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
