<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Informant no longer overseeing Virginia boxing  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- For nearly two decades, the regulation of
professional boxing and wrestling events in Virginia was handled by
a retired Navy corpsman, C. Douglas ''Doc'' Beavers.
</P>
<P>
   That reign ended last month as Beavers, who was also the
longtime ratings chairman for the International Boxing Federation,
began testifying that he and IBF founder Robert W. Lee took bribes
to rig the boxer ratings.
</P>
<P>
   His testimony was no surprise. Boxing insiders have long
suspected that Beavers was cooperating with the FBI corruption
probe, and a 59-page sworn statement by Beavers outlining years of
bribery became public Jan. 28.
</P>
<P>
   A Virginia official said the state did not learn of the
statement until a reporter called in April.
</P>
<P>
   That statement has served as a road map in the prosecution of
Lee, with Beavers outlining payoffs from some of boxing's biggest
promoters, including Don King and Cedric Kushner.
</P>
<P>
   The East Orange-based IBF is one of boxing's three major
sanctioning organizations, and its rankings play a big role in
determining whom a boxer fights, and his purse.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony over the past month in Lee's trial in Newark,
Beavers, 56, of Portsmouth, Va., described dozens of payments and
led the jury through 83 covertly made tapes of his conversations
and meetings with Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Beavers became executive director of the Virginia Athletic
Commission in 1981, succeeding a friend, IBF championship committee
chairman Bill Brennan, of Warsaw, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The agency regulated boxing and wrestling in the state until
1995, when those functions were contracted to a private company
owned by Beavers, the Virginia Boxing and Wrestling Association
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia suspended the contract April 17, and ended it on April
19, the day Beavers began his testimony, said Doug McCartney, chief
deputy director for the Virginia Department of Professional and
Occupational Regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Beavers remained on the stand Thursday, his fifth day of
cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   McCartney on Wednesday said Virginia learned of Beavers' sworn
statement in April when a reporter called. He said the state had no
knowledge prior to that of Beavers' activities.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is frustrating to us that the feds couldn't tell us what
was going on,'' McCartney said. ''Obviously, they were trying to
protect their investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The contract with the Virginia Boxing and Wrestling Association
gave Beavers 95 percent of the state's 5 percent take on all sales
in professional boxing and wrestling matches in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Beavers' company received $156,000 in 1999 and the first three
months of 2000, McCartney said. Beavers had to pay his expenses out
of that money.
</P>
<P>
   Beavers had testified that wrestling provided the bulk of the
company's income.
</P>
<P>
   There is no indication that Beavers engaged in any illegal
activities in his capacity as a Virginia regulator, McCartney said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The observations were that Mr. Beavers ran a tight ship,''
McCartney said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, the state had no good reason to drop Beavers'
company, said Beavers' attorney, Joel Weintraub.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's our position that they didn't have cause to terminate the
contract,'' Weintraub said.
</P>
<P>
   The state has the right to terminate the contract for any
reason, but must provide 120 days' notice unless it has good cause,
Weintraub said. He suggested Beavers may be entitled to
compensation because the contract was canceled without notice.
</P>
<P>
   For the last month, the state has done its own regulation of
boxing and wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's probably no chance that we're ever going to contract
it out again,'' McCartney said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, 66, of Fanwood, was indicted in November with three other
IBF officials, accused of taking $338,000 in payoffs to rig
rankings and provide favors since 1983, when he founded the IBF.
</P>
<P>
   Lee took a leave of absence in December, and the IBF is being
run by another federation official under the watch of a
court-appointed monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Lee and his son, Robert Jr., 38, of Scotch Plains, are the only
defendants on trial. They face multiyear prison terms if convicted
on conspiracy, racketeering, fraud and tax charges.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan, 86, of Warsaw, Va., past president of the U.S. Boxing
Association, a group that became the IBF, was severed from the
trial due to ill health.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth defendant, Francisco Fernandez of Colombia, the IBF's
South American representative, remains at large.
</P>
<P>
   The trial before U.S. District Judge John W. Bissell began April
11 and is expected to last about two more months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
