<DOCNO> APW20000518.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Signs African Trade Bill  </HEADLINE>
By SONYA ROSS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Declaring that trade ''must work for all
people,'' President Clinton signed Thursday legislation that opens
U.S. markets to more goods from poor African, Caribbean and Central
American nations.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by smiling members of Congress, the president signed
the Trade and Development Act of 2000 from a small wooden desk atop
an oversized stage on the White House South Lawn. Afterward, a
military band played ''The Impossible Dream'' while Clinton mingled
happily among the lawmakers for so long that all but a few went
indoors without him.
</P>
<P>
   ''This day has been a long time coming. But it is here,''
Clinton said. ''We must not avoid our neighbors in Central America
and the Caribbean, or our friends half a world away in Africa. We
must build a better future, together, with both.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the legislation was really about ending,
officially, the Cold War notion that ''Central America was a
battleground and Africa was a backwater.''
</P>
<P>
   ''All that has changed,'' Clinton said. ''Our agenda for the
developing world must be multifaceted, recognizing that trade must
work for all people, and that spirited competition should lift all
nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Mel Foote, executive director of the advocacy group Constituency
for Africa, said while the new law does not fully redeem the flaws
in Clinton's Africa policy, it does establish a mechanism for
pushing improvements through Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a first step. We can't look at the job as done,'' Foote
said. ''We all know there are weaknesses in the bill. But this bill
sets the framework in which we are engaged with Africa, and that's
very important.''
</P>
<P>
   About 350 people attended the ceremony, including African
diplomats, House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., and the mayors of
Detroit and Atlanta. It took place just after Clinton met privately
with former South African President Nelson Mandela, who updated
Clinton on his efforts to negotiate an end to civil war in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Thursday's good news about trade was tempered by
sad circumstances in Africa, such as unrest in Sierra Leone and the
resumption by Ethiopia and Eritrea of ''their senseless war.'' He
appealed to those nations to step back from conflict and reach for
peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''Backing away from self-destruction is not the same thing as
backing down,'' Clinton said. ''Giving your people a future is not
cowardice, it's common sense and courage.''
</P>
<P>
   It took five years for the trade bill to move through Congress.
The legislation was combined with a Caribbean initiative and passed
last week on a 77-19 Senate vote, the first major trade legislation
approved since a 1994 bill that led to creation of the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're still in love with Europe, but Africa is on the map,''
said Rep. Charlie Rangel, D-N.Y., ranking member of the Ways and
Means Committee. ''For those of us that come from multiracial
communities, this bill means so much, because our young people can
identify now with all parts of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   During his historic 1998 tour of Africa, Clinton touted the
trade bill as a means through which the poorest African countries
could build their own economies, reduce their debts and stabilize
their governments.
</P>
<P>
   ''It (is) a beautiful day of hope for peace, for opportunity,
for a better way of life for so many millions of additional people
around the world,'' said House Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer,
R-Texas. ''That's what America should stand for.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, countries can ship, duty-free, clothing made
with U.S. yarn and fabrics, provided they meet certain human rights
and labor standards.
</P>
<P>
   Clothing made in Africa from African fabric would be allowed to
rise from 1.5 percent of U.S. imports to 3.5 percent over eight
years, boosting African exports of these products from about $250
million a year now to as much as $4.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   African nations whose gross domestic product is less than $1,500
a year per person -- all but six of the 48 sub-Saharan nations --
would have four years of quota-free benefits for apparel made with
third-country fabric.
</P>
<P>
   The inclusion of Caribbean nations helps level the trade playing
field that tilted in Mexico's favor after the North American Free
Trade Agreement went into effect.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The White House Briefing Room, for bill summary:
www.whitehouse.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
