<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded
heavily Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock
Market.
</P>
<P>
NYSE
</P>
<P>
Sprint Corp., down 1} at 56\
</P>
<P>
   Federal antitrust enforcers have recommended blocking WorldCom
Inc.'s $115 billion buyout of Sprint Corp. because it would violate
antitrust law, The Wall Street Journal reported today.
</P>
<P>
Toyota Motor, up 7[ at 98
</P>
<P>
   The automaker said profits for the fiscal year ended March 31
rose 14.2 percent from a year earlier. Toyota saw record demand in
North America and other export markets, selling more than 3 million
vehicles overseas for the first time ever.
</P>
<P>
National Discount Brokers Group Inc., up 3{ at 28
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank AG and Internet brokerage National Discount
Brokers moved their proposed alliance another step forward by
signing a definitive stock purchase agreement. Deutsche Bank is
taking a 14.3 percent stake in NDB.
</P>
<P>
Equant NV, down 14{ at 46~
</P>
<P>
   The company, a provider of data network services, reported a
first-quarter loss of 12 cents per share, compared with profits of
4 cents per share a year ago. Merrill Lynch cut its rating on the
stock to neutral from accumulate.
</P>
<P>
NASDAQ
</P>
<P>
Petco Animal Supplies Inc., up 4 11/16 at 19|
</P>
<P>
   The company agreed to be acquired Wednesday by two private
banking firms, for an estimated $464.2 million in cash, or $22 per
share. The firms will also assume about $136 million in Petco debt.
The transaction will take Petco private.
</P>
<P>
Phone.com Inc., down 2{ at 81
</P>
<P>
   The mobile Internet software provider raised its fourth-quarter
revenue expectations to $24 million to $25 million, up from earlier
estimates of $22 million to $23 million, and raised its fiscal 2001
revenue expectations. Shares reversed an early gain.
</P>
<P>
Legato Systems Inc., down 4 1/16 at 11 15/16
</P>
<P>
   Legato, a maker of network storage management software, restated
its financial results for the first three quarters of 1999. As
previously reported, Legato discovered that some employees had
entered into unauthorized side agreements with resellers that
altered the recognition of revenue.
</P>
<P>
Gymboree Corp., down ] at 2{
</P>
<P>
   The children's apparel company lost 56 cents per share in the
first quarter, reversing a gain of 20 cents per share in the first
quarter of 1999. Same-store sales plummeted 24 percent as Gymboree
stocked what it now calls inappropriate inventory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
