<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Ends Down 106; Dow Up 8  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks meandered to a mixed finish Thursday as
investors failed to find direction in a market facing rising
interest rates and a dearth of significant economic news.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market is just marking time,'' said Alan Ackerman, senior
vice president at Fahnestock &AMP; Co. in New York. ''We have buyers
and sellers just waiting it out for the time being.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 7.54 to close at
10,777.28. Earlier in the session, the index had been up as much as
95 points.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Nasdaq composite
index fell 106.25 to 3,538.71, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell
10.59 to 1,437.21.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq's largest technology stocks led the index lower
Thursday. Cisco Systems fell 2| to 55], Oracle lost 5[ to 73 1/16
and Microsoft slipped 1{ to 66 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint fell 1} to 56\ and WorldCom fell 2 7/16 to 39 9/16. The
Wall Street Journal reported that federal antitrust enforcers have
recommended blocking WorldCom's $115 billion buyout of Sprint
because it would violate antitrust law.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that while investors haven't truly turned against
technology stocks, there's little interest in buying into the
volatile sector while interest rates are rising.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lot of cash out there, and yet we see only very
selective buying,'' said Donald Berdine, chief investment officer
at PNC Advisors. ''There's very, very little conviction, and very
few heroes to step up.''
</P>
<P>
   Lycos rose 4 45/64 to 62 5/16. After the close of trading
Wednesday, the company reported better-than-expected results for
its fiscal third quarter. Analysts said investors remain wary of
the stock due to concerns about the proposed takeover of Lycos by
Spain's Terra Networks SA.
</P>
<P>
   The broader market was fairly quiet as investors sought a new
path in a market facing higher interest rates. The Federal Reserve
raised rates for the sixth time since June on Tuesday, pushing the
federal funds rate -- the interest that banks charge each other for
overnight loans -- to 6.5 percent, the highest level in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   Escalating borrowing costs make it tougher to borrow money to
finance growth. Ultimately, that can cut into corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a lingering case of interest rate jitters,'' Ackerman
said. ''There are not many who believe the Fed is near the end of
its rate hikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, financial stocks, which are vulnerable to interest rate
fluctuations, were modestly higher. J.P. Morgan rose 15/16 to 133
9/16 and Merrill Lynch rose 1 1/16 to 109 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   ''People have said unilaterally that that they don't want to own
financial stocks while interest rates are moving higher,'' Berdine
said. ''As a result, many of them are now very reasonably priced.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said it could take several weeks before the market
breaks out of a narrow range. Investors now face a dry spell of
major economic reports, with little to indicate whether the long
series of rate increases are successfully slowing the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the Labor Department's weekly jobless claims report
showed that new claims for unemployment benefits fell last week for
the second week in a row. That suggested companies are still
scrambling to find workers, leaving themselves vulnerable to
pressure to bump up wages and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The next economic report with significant market-moving
potential is due May 25, when the Commerce Department issues its
preliminary report on first-quarter gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-4 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 986.89 million
shares, compared with 980.57 million the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   Volume, which has been running low for the past two weeks, could
spike on Friday, which is a ''double witching'' session. Stock and
index options positions will expire, which typically causes a rush
of large orders to buy or sell.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 8.71 to 490.95.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 2.1 percent.
Germany's Xetra DAX index fell 0.4 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100
rose 0.6 percent, and France's CAC-40 fell 0.02 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
