<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appellate decision erodes distinction between libel and slander  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- A ruling by the state Superior Court's
Appellate Division erodes the distinction between print and
broadcast media when it comes to defamation cases.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, defamation suits against radio and television
stations were tried as slander cases. Newspapers, magazines and
other print outlets were subjected to libel standards, which
require plaintiffs to show actual damage to their reputations.
</P>
<P>
   An appellate court ruling on Wednesday erases that distinction,
under which libel carries a higher burden of proof for damages, and
sets a precedent in which all media would be considered equal.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Cafferty, an attorney who represents the New Jersey Press
Association, hailed the court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should applaud the language of this case, which would
indicate that a plantiff in a defamation action must establish by
concrete evidence '' there was damage to his reputation, said
Cafferty, who is also chair of the New Jersey State Bar
Association's Media Law Committee.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the court reversed a 1998 jury decision in favor
of Camden County Sheriff Michael M. McLaughlin in his defamation
case against William Simon, his opponent in the 1994 sheriff's
race, and RB&AMP;T, a Cherry Hill advertising agency that produced
radio spots for Simon's campaign, because McLaughlin's case was
tried under slander laws.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are of the view that slander per se is on its last legs in
New Jersey, and may no longer be viable ... basis for awarding
damages when there is no demonstrable harm,'' the decision reads.
</P>
<P>
   A Burlington County jury awarded McLaughlin $40,000 in
compensatory damages and $500,000 in punitive damages. Simon and
RB&AMP;T were ordered to split the payments. Simon and McLaughlin
settled shortly after the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The slander suit concerned a radio advertisement during the
hotly contested race.
</P>
<P>
   The ad said McLaughlin, a former New Jersey State Police
intelligence officer, had leaked confidential information to an
organized crime family during an investigation. Simon had approved
the script, which said: ''... how far can you trust a man who
breaks the rules of the New Jersey State Police ... and then tries
to cover it up?''
</P>
<P>
   The appellate court did not dispute that Simon and RB&AMP;T defamed
McLaughlin. It disputed the standard of slander, saying McLaughlin
did not produce enough evidence of the harm done to his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the court noted that McLaughlin handily won the
sheriff's race, and that many of his supporters called him to say
they did not believe the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ''This brings New Jersey into line with other jurisdictions and
more modern trend of thought,'' said Richard S. Hyland, the Cherry
Hill attorney who represented RB&AMP;T. ''This is a significant
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin's attorney, William Tambussi, said Thursday that he
would appeal the decision to the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ''The net effect of this ruling is that the only way a
politician who is defamed with malice can win a case, is if he or
she loses the election,'' Tambussi said. ''You will now see more
scurrilous and insubstantial ads from fringe candidates, who,
unless they beat them, won't be held liable.''
</P>
<P>
   ''A check on negative campaigning has been eliminated by virtue
of a technicality on the distinction between libel and slander,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-18-00 1840 </TRAILER>
