<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Task force seeks subpoena power in auto emissions probe  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- After several members said they couldn't do
the job without it, a task force investigating a $400 million
contract to privatize auto emissions tests agreed Thursday to ask
the state Senate for subpoena powers to aid in the probe.
</P>
<P>
   But a defiant Senate President Donald T. DiFrancesco, R-Union,
refused to act and demanded that the task force begin its hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to give it to them when they need it,'' DiFrancesco
said of the subpoena power.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very upset they haven't had a hearing,'' DiFrancesco said.
He created the task force in February and there has yet to be any
public meeting on the contract with Parsons Infrastructure and
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to hear some testimony. I want to hear some facts,''
DiFrancesco said.
</P>
<P>
   Only the full state Senate has the ability to grant a committee
subpoena powers. As it stands now, the task force is simply an
advisory body. Unless DiFrancesco puts the issue up for a vote, the
Senate cannot act.
</P>
<P>
   Both Democratic senators on the task force tried to force the
issue before the full Senate on Thursday. Other senators ignored
them and proceeded to the next item on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco ordered the task force to investigate what led to
the deal with Parsons, a seven-year contract that is estimated to
cost taxpayers $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   Problems began once Parsons was on the job in December. Foul-ups
in computer programs and testing systems forced motorists to wait
hours at inspection stations.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitman administration blames Parsons, while the company
says New Jersey officials are partially at fault.
</P>
<P>
   Recent audits show testing equipment that failed in winter
weather could again malfunction in high temperatures. Earlier tests
prompted the state to halt tougher emissions test and the use of a
complicated computer system at 15 of the state's 32 inspection
lanes to allow Parsons time to make improvements.
</P>
<P>
   All members of the task force -- Republicans and Democrats alike,
as well as a former U.S. district court judge -- voted to seek the
subpoena power.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just not prepared to sit in with all this unless we're
prepared to be an authentic and investigative body,'' said Herbert
J. Stern. Stern, one of two public members appointed to the
committee, was a former U.S. Attorney, as well as a federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   ''Either we're going to be a real committee and do a real job or
we're not,'' Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Wayne Bryant, D-Camden, said he would think twice about
sitting on the task force without the power to compel witnesses to
testify.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Norm Robertson, R-Passaic, said he has assurances from
the governor's office and other state executives that they will
cooperate. Robertson said Thursday he has received word that
documents, possibly as many as 100,000 pages, will be produced.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't care whether or not they are cooperating, it is a
difference when people are under oath,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   After failing to win support from the Senate, Sen. Garry
Furnari, D-Essex, promised to petition again for the subpoena
power.
</P>
<P>
   ''This issue is not going to rest,'' Furnari said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Senate task force, the state Attorney
General's Office began a probe in January. In March, retired state
Supreme Court Justice Alan Handler was appointed to lead that
investigation after Attorney General John J. Farmer Jr. cited a
conflict of interest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
