<HEADLINE> Israeli Forces Pound South Lebanon  </HEADLINE>
By HUSSEIN DAKROUB
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Israeli air and ground forces attacked
guerrilla bases in southern Lebanon on Thursday, leaving one
militant dead and five people wounded, Lebanese security officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Jerusalem, a top aide to Prime Minister Ehud Barak
acknowledged Thursday that Israel's withdrawal from Lebanon,
promised by July 7, is being driven by public pressure to end
Israeli casualties there.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah has stepped up attacks in recent weeks as Israel
begins to dismantle its positions in preparation for a complete
withdrawal. The attacks have prompted harsh Israeli retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   Israel announced three Israeli soldiers were injured and a
soldier of the Israeli-allied South Lebanon Army was slightly hurt
in strikes overnight and early Thursday by Shiite Muslim guerrillas
in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The Shiite Hezbollah group said one of its guerrillas was killed
in the fighting near the port of Tyre.
</P>
<P>
   A shell fired by the pro-Israeli South Lebanon Army exploded in
the village of Mansouri, wounding a 34-year-old woman, her
daughter, 8, and son, 6, Lebanese officials said on condition of
not using their names.
</P>
<P>
   A Fijian soldier in the U.N. peacekeeping force suffered
shrapnel wounds in the same village when another shell hit his
position, a U.N. officer said, speaking on the same condition of
not being named.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday, Hezbollah guerrillas attacked several outposts
manned by Israeli troops and the South Lebanon Army in
Israeli-occupied southern Lebanon, according to a Hezbollah
statement and an Israeli army spokesman in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   One South Lebanon Army militiaman was slightly wounded, Israeli
and Lebanese officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli jets and helicopters fired missiles at guerrilla targets
near Tyre, the town of Nabatiyeh and in the Hezbollah mountain
stronghold of Iqlim al-Tuffah, Lebanese security officials said.
</P>
<P>
   They said Israeli missiles also hit targets in Ein el-Tineh and
Birket Jabbour on the edge of the occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, the U.N. forces stopped their movements between
Naqoura, where the U.N. headquarters are located, and southern
Lebanon after a South Lebanese Army commander threatened to open
fire on all U.N. vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The 4,500 U.N. peacekeepers have been in Lebanon since the 1978
Israeli invasion, which led to Israel's occupying a swath of south
Lebanon to protect northern Israeli towns from cross-border
guerrilla attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
