<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US, Mexico To Combat Alien Smuggling  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States and Mexico agreed Thursday
to intensify efforts to curb the smuggling of Mexican migrants into
Arizona and their illegal detention by vigilante groups once they
cross the border.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was announced at the close of a day-long meeting
of senior officials from both countries.
</P>
<P>
   A joint statement said the two governments committed themselves
to ''strengthen efforts to monitor, investigate and, if warranted,
prosecute'' unlawful behavior by private citizens or law
enforcement authorities on both sides of the border.
</P>
<P>
   They also promised to intensify separate and joint efforts to
combat criminal organizations of migrant smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   Serving as co-chairs of the meeting of the U.S.-Mexico
Binational Commission were Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
and Mexican Foreign Secretary Rosario Green.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Albright said the two countries ''are
cooperating more closely than ever before on counter-narcotics
matters'' and are ''determined to intensify our joint efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   But Green earlier expressed concern about the ''intolerant
expressions of some American ranchers who promote the persecution
of migrants along the border.'' Green has cited 32 incidents of
vigilante acts committed against Mexican immigrants in the United
States since January 1994 including 27 were in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Mexico hired a U.S. law firm to help gather
evidence and bring charges against Arizona ranchers, claiming that
they illegally detained immigrants in vigilante actions.
</P>
<P>
   A report this week by KOLD television station in Tucson, Ariz.,
showed a ranch hand detaining five men, apparently illegal
immigrants, and holding them at gunpoint for the arrival of the
U.S. Border Patrol. A ranch worker was shown pushing one of the men
from a seated position onto his stomach.
</P>
<P>
   In southern Arizona, ranchers in the Douglas area started
patrolling their properties in force when the number of illegal
immigrants crossing into that region jumped dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Ranchers say illegal immigrants crossing their land cut their
water lines and litter their properties. According to one report, a
group of ranchers distributed flyers inviting people ''to hunt
undocumented Mexicans.''
</P>
<P>
   On the narcotics issue, Green reaffirmed Mexico's disagreement
with the annual process whereby the United States evaluates the
counter-drug performance of countries that produce drugs or are
used as transit points for traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has routinely certified Mexico as
fully cooperating in counter-drug efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But a critical analysis of the Mexican effort was offered Monday
in congressional testimony by William Ledwith, a top official of
the Drug Enforcement Administration.
</P>
<P>
   He said powerful Mexican drug traffickers have been able to
avoid arrest because of their ability ''to intimidate witnesses,
assassinate public officials and corrupt many of the civilian law
enforcement agencies in Mexico, often at the command level.''
</P>
<P>
   Ledwith also said the DEA is ''extremely concerned'' about the
Mexican government's ability to ensure the safety of DEA agents in
Mexico.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-18-00 1905 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000518.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Christians Freed in Vietnam Amnesty  </HEADLINE>
By TINI TRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) -- Two Christian dissidents were among the
more than 12,000 prisoners released in a mass amnesty last month,
Vietnamese officials confirmed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The two -- a Catholic clergyman and a member of a Protestant sect
-- were freed along with 12,262 others in the country's largest
pardoning ever, marking the 25th anniversary of the end of the
Vietnam War on April 30, the Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam has repeatedly said that no political dissidents are
being held. However, the country's broadly worded national security
law has been used to clamp down on spiritual movements not approved
by the government and to silence political dissent.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Human Rights Watch released a 34-page report
detailing Vietnam's continuing repression of critics, who are
routinely subjected to harassment, restrictions on travel and
communications, house arrest and imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based rights group named the two Christian
dissidents -- Catholic clergyman Brother John Euder Mai Duc Chuong,
64, and Protestant sect member Vu Gian Thao, 32 -- among those who
had been jailed for religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Chuong, also known as Mai Huu Nghi, a member of the Congregation
of the Mother Co-Redemptrix, was arrested in 1987 for disrupting
public security and ''conducting propaganda to oppose the socialist
regime and undermining the policy of unity.'' He was sentenced to
18 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Thao, a member of the Hmong ethnic minority from the northern
province of Lai Chau, was arrested in 1997 for ''abusing religious
freedom and infringing on the state's rights.'' Thao was sentenced
to three years.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, officials confirmed that Vietnamese journalist Nguyen
Ngoc Tan, who spent five years in jail for advocating human rights,
also was released in the amnesty.
</P>
<P>
   Tan, 80, who used the pen name Pham Thai, was an activist in the
unofficial Movement for the Unity of the People and Construction of
Democracy and also pushed for press freedom. Arrested in 1995, Tan
was sentenced to 11 years for ''conspiring against socialist
power.''
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups estimate Vietnam holds at least 40 religious
or political dissidents prisoner. Among those being singled out are
senior party officials who have advocated political reform,
religious leaders, intellectuals and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   According to state prison statistics, there are more than 100
people convicted of crimes against national security, the Human
Rights Watch report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-18-00 1907 </TRAILER>
