<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Warrant Issued in Fireworks Blast  </HEADLINE>
By JOHAN VAN DER TOL
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENSCHEDE, Netherlands (AP) -- An international arrest warrant was
issued Thursday for the owners of a fireworks warehouse that
exploded last weekend, killing at least 20 people and wounding
almost 1,000, Dutch media reported.
</P>
<P>
   Television stations said Rudi Bakker and Wilhelm Pater are
wanted on suspicion of ''responsibility for possible illegal
activities'' by the S.E. Fireworks firm. The reports said police
searched the suspects' homes and offices Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The warehouse caught fire Saturday afternoon, sparking a
firestorm from 100 tons of explosives that left several city blocks
looking like a war zone. More than 600 people were injured.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said earlier this week that the two owners had
contacted them through their lawyer and promised to cooperate with
the investigation. But the whereabouts of the suspects remained a
mystery. One newspaper reported that Bakker was in a hospital in
neighboring Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities could not be reached to confirm the reports.
</P>
<P>
   At least 21 people were still missing after detectives tracked
down hundreds of people in the days since the blast, Jan Cryns of
the Disaster Victim Identification Team said Thursday. A list of
their names was broadcast on national television.
</P>
<P>
   Police were overwhelmed with reports of 4,400 missing after the
blast, and called in reinforcements to help track down those
unaccounted for and quell fears that the death toll exceeded by far
the official figure.
</P>
<P>
   Since Tuesday, a 70-member task force worked to whittle down the
list.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Jan Mans said rescue workers expected to finish sifting
through the remains of some 400 houses by the weekend. The
explosion flattened several rows of houses, wounding 945 people.
</P>
<P>
   Dutch and German media have speculated that the death toll could
be significantly higher than the official toll of 20, which has not
changed since several hours after Saturday's blast.
</P>
<P>
   Fire Chief Aad Groos suggested the figure was a reliable
estimate after the recovery of 18 bodies. ''All other figures are
speculation,'' Groos said.
</P>
<P>
   But regional Police Chief Aad Meyboom raised the possibility
that more victims be uncovered in a basement now buried under 660
pounds of rubble.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hard work is being done, based on practical detective
information ... to look into the possibility that victims may still
be found,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
