<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Networks May Skip Clinton Address  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton's speech Sunday night
promoting a U.S-China trade deal will air live on only one of the
three major television networks.
</P>
<P>
   CBS and ABC said Thursday they will not carry the speech,
despite a request from the White House. NBC, CNN and FOX will air a
live broadcast of the five-minute address.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of internal debate, the White House announced
Thursday morning that Clinton would make a nationally televised
address on the China deal -- the last major trade fight of his
administration and a significant legislative victory if the
Republican-led Congress passes it next week.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the president thinks that this is an extremely
important issue. He wants to make sure that he has a chance to
articulate why a positive vote ... is in our economic and national
security interests,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   CBS decided the speech amounted to lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   ''Normally the White House asks for time in prime time when it
is a matter of national security,'' CBS spokeswoman Sandy Genelius
said. ''This seemed to us more like part of the political debate on
this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS will make the speech available to any local affiliate that
chooses to broadcast it live, Genelius said.
</P>
<P>
   ABC spokeswoman Su-Lin Nichols said the network decided against
a live broadcast because ''it has already covered very thoroughly
both sides of this issue on our news programs, and we will continue
to cover the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC spokeswoman Barbara Levin said the network will pre-empt a
movie to broadcast Clinton's remarks ''on an issue of national
importance.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think both the president and the congressional leadership
feel strongly on this issue. We've decided to honor the request,''
Levin said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's speech comes as Congress is set to debate the trade
bill, which would open Chinese markets to more U.S. goods and end
annual review of China's trading status. The deal is opposed by
organized labor and many environmental and human rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   The impetus for a speech to the nation came in part from members
of Congress who wanted Clinton to take the case directly to their
constituents, Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the speech is an attempt to give wavering members
''political cover,'' Lockhart said no.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is also responding to ... a number of members of Congress
who indicated it would be useful for him to go and make the case,
you know, in the most public way you can,'' Lockhart said, ''And
that is to talk to the country from the Oval Office.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton asked for, and got, national television time for four
previous speeches on pending legislation, Lockhart said. The last
was in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-18-00 1934 </TRAILER>
