<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deal Reached on Border Crossings  </HEADLINE>
By NEDRA PICKLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two lawmakers want a national computer
database of information collected whenever agents conduct spot
check questioning of foreigners at U.S. border points.
</P>
<P>
   In introducing the idea, Sen. Spence Abraham, R-Mich., and Rep.
Lamar Smith, R-Texas, hope to block a law that was set to go into
effect next year that would require border agents to question and
keep track of every foreigner who travels in and out of the
country. That law said everyone should be questioned but didn't
specify how that information should be recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham and Smith have disagreed for years over how to better
enforce U.S. immigration and customs laws at border crossings
without bottling up traffic. But together Thursday, they announced
legislation that they say will accomplish both goals. The measure
was introduced in the House, and is expected to be introduced in
the Senate early next week.
</P>
<P>
   The original law --Section 110 of the Illegal Immigration Reform
and Immigrant Responsibility Act -- was designed to stop visitors
from staying in the United States longer than their visas allow.
</P>
<P>
   But many business groups and lawmakers from states along the
Canadian border worried that it would create massive delays and
slow international commerce and tourism.
</P>
<P>
   ''It just would have been economic chaos if the original
legislation would have been enacted,'' said Dick Blouse, president
and CEO of the Detroit Regional Chamber of Commerce. ''There's
13,500 trucks a day that go back and forth a day between Detroit
and Windsor (in Canada). They estimate those trucks would have been
backed up 17 hours if this legislation was enacted.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has voted three times to repeal the law, but the
House has yet to go along. Congressional and White House
negotiators agreed in 1998 to delay the law's original start until
2001, giving the INS time to come up with a workable plan.
</P>
<P>
   The deal reached by Abraham, who led opposition to the law, and
Smith, the leading supporter, does not call for the Immigration and
Naturalization Service to collect any more information from
foreigners than is currently collected by agents on pieces of
paper, such as name, country of origin and date of birth.
</P>
<P>
   However, the information that is collected would now be kept in
a computerized database that would allow immigration and law
enforcement agents to have continuous access to the information.
</P>
<P>
   ''For people crossing the border, they are going to see very
little difference,'' said Smith spokesman Allen Kay.
</P>
<P>
   Kay said without the database, border agents have no way of
knowing if the person they are allowing to enter the country is
wanted by the FBI or other law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the INS released illegal immigrant Angel Maturino
Resendiz back to Mexico, not knowing he was wanted by the FBI,
Texas Rangers and Houston police for questioning about murders near
rail lines in this country. He was later captured on charges of
killing nine people in three states.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement would require air and sea ports to enter
information into the database by Dec. 31, 2003. The 50 busiest land
border crossings would be required to have the system installed by
the end of 2004 and the rest of the crossings by the end of 2005.
</P>
<P>
   It also calls for the creation of a government and industry task
force to examine the needs and costs of any additional measures at
borders.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bottom line is that we will have a system that enhances
law enforcement capabilities and will not impose new or onerous
requirements on travelers that would damage Americans or the
American economy,'' Abraham said.
</P>
<P>
   INS spokeswoman Eileen Schmidt said Thursday that the agency was
reviewing the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.ins.usdoj.gov
</P>
<P>
   http://www.uschamber.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
