<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AM-NJ--Floyd-Business Losses, Bjt,600  </HEADLINE>
By WAYNE PARRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOUND BROOK, N.J. (AP) -- Local governments in communities
ravaged by Tropical Storm Floyd last year should consider cutting
or forgiving property and sales taxes for flood-damaged businesses
that commit to rebuild, a federal report suggested Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the Federal Emergency Management Agency and the
U.S. Economic Development Administration also urged communities to
move critical facilities like hospitals, police and fire stations,
power plants and utilities out of flood plains, or take measures to
better protect them from rising flood waters.
</P>
<P>
   The report estimated the damage to New Jersey businesses at $127
million, most of it in the hardest-hit communities of Bound Brook
($77 million); Passaic ($17 million); Lodi ($12 million); Trenton
($9 million); Paterson ($8 million) and Manville ($3 million).
</P>
<P>
   The tax waiver proposal would need the approval of state and
local officials, and FEMA officials did not recommend how long the
break should remain in effect. But some hard-hit merchants said it
would be one of the quickest ways to help them recover from
thousands of dollars in debt incurred by the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it would be fantastic,'' said Stan Biniek, whose shoe
store on East Main Street in Bound Brook was wiped out by the
flood. ''We need all the help we can get, and that would be a big
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Saving all or part of the $2,700 a year he pays in property
taxes would help him dig out from about $170,000 in losses Biniek
sustained when the Raritan River spilled over onto East Main Street
and inundated his store, which specializes in orthopedic shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ''This one I took on the chin,'' he said. ''We lost everything,
from the floor right up to the ceiling. We lost our entire
inventory, we had to put in new floors, new ceilings, new air
conditioning, wiring, a furnace. The day before the flood, we got a
shipment of $12,000 worth of work boots, still in the cartons,
never touched.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends in the construction business agreed to defer billing him
for work on his store, but shoe manufacturers didn't want to hear
about any flood, he said. He took out a $70,000 loan from FEMA,
which still must be repaid.
</P>
<P>
   Bound Brook Mayor Frank J. Ryan said his borough already has
provided tax relief for the approximately 840 businesses and homes
damaged in the storm, lowering property tax assessments by about 20
percent. He said he does not know if the government could afford to
take in any less tax money.
</P>
<P>
   ''We lost $45 million in ratables as a result of the storm,'' he
said. ''We just got clobbered.''
</P>
<P>
   The borough is lobbying Gov. Christie Whitman for $3.9 million
in discretionary state aid this year to help recover from the
flood.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Herman, a spokesman for the governor, could not say whether
Whitman was likely to endorse the tax waiver proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ''We share the goal of reducing the economic impact of the
storm, and will carefully review the recommendations of the
report,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone thinks the tax waiver is the best way to help
struggling merchants. Randy Fender's bar, the Pour Man's Pub on
South Main Street in Manville was wrecked by the flood, and he has
grown disillusioned with FEMA.
</P>
<P>
   He estimated he lost between $30,000 and $40,000 in the flood,
which he paid for out of his own pocket. A tax waiver wouldn't help
him because he leases the building from a commercial landlord. And
he said FEMA's application process was so daunting he simply gave
up.
</P>
<P>
   ''I need a grant, but they won't give me one,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
