<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru's Toledo Won't Enter Runoff  </HEADLINE>
By MONTE HAYES
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Alejandro Toledo announced Thursday he will
not participate in the May 28 runoff against President Alberto
Fujimori, and he called for a postponement to resolve alleged
election irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have come to tell you that Peru Possible will not
participate in the election on May 28,'' Toledo said at a news
conference, referring to the name of his political movement. ''We
have requested an extension until June 18.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he would not participate in a runoff on June 18 if
the election irregularities that marked the first round were not
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, a U.S.-trained economist, had repeatedly warned that he
will pull out of the race if conditions did not improve.
</P>
<P>
   Hours earlier, protesters yelling ''Get out, tyrant!'' stoned
Fujimori's vehicle at a campaign rally in Ayacucho on Thursday
after the Organization of American States demanded a postponement
of Peru's election runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's bodyguards fired automatic rifles into the air to
drive back dozens of demonstrators who ran after his pickup truck
hurling stones and shouting insults as he pulled away from the
plaza in Ayacucho, high in the Andes 230 miles southeast of Lima.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters appeared to be students from the state university
in Ayacucho, the birthplace of the Shining Path insurgency that
bloodied this Andean nation through the 1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The windshield of Fujimori's pickup was cracked by thrown rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes earlier, Fujimori had ended a campaign speech to
thousands of supporters gathered in the plaza, including
Quechua-speaking peasants trucked in from the countryside to hear
him.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori promised to build roads and irrigation systems as a way
of creating jobs in an area that saw the worst of the guerrilla
violence until rebel leaders were captured in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters before boarding a plane back to Lima,
Fujimori condemned the stone throwing and rejected an OAS request
for postponement the runoff. The OAS said it was necessary to put
off the polls to avoid a repeat of the fraud that plagued the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   In its strongest statement yet, the OAS said it was giving
Fujimori's government until Monday, after a nationwide test of the
election authority's vote counting software, to make necessary
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot endorse the results'' of the runoff ''if what
happened in the first round continues,'' said Eduardo Stein, chief
of an OAS mission of election observers.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the OAS request, Fujimori said: ''We can't change
the rules at this stage of the process.'' The Peruvian president
has refused to postpone the runoff election, saying it was set by
constitution guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Peru narrowly avoided political turmoil after the first round
vote on April 9, when election officials announced that Fujimori
had fallen a hair shy of the absolute majority needed to win
another five-year term.
</P>
<P>
   The result came amid intense international pressure for a
second-round vote, including threatened sanctions from the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Independent monitors were denied access to tabulation centers
during the vote tally. Ballot totals mysteriously decreased as the
tally progressed and when the final results were delivered, the
figures showed about 1 million more ballots were cast than there
were voters.
</P>
<P>
   Stein on Wednesday complained that Peruvian officials handed his
mission an incomplete copy of vote-counting software for the
upcoming election. And he said that he was still waiting for a
promised report detailing how election officials plan to train vote
counters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-18-00 2007 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000518.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate passes $15 billion school construction bill  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Two years after the state Supreme Court
ordered New Jersey to pay to replace crumbling and overcrowded
school buildings in 30 of the poorest districts, legislation
funding the program is finally heading toward the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday passed, by a 36-1 vote, the huge school
construction bill.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which has evolved into a catchall for affluent
suburban schools as well, comes with an estimated $15 billion price
tag over 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation has an uncertain future, however. A
substantially different version is scheduled for action next month
in the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Jack Collins on Thursday pledged to pass a bill
by the Supreme Court's spring deadline. Yet, the bill's final form
is far from clear.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's Senate passage sets the stage for what promises to be
weeks of intense negotiations among Collins, Senate President
Donald DiFrancesco and Gov. Christie Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   One major point of contention involves facilities funding for
the special needs districts.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate version provides 100 percent funding for all projects
in the poor schools, in keeping with the court ruling that most
interpret as ordering full funding.
</P>
<P>
   But the Assembly bill provides full funding only for emergency
repairs and for projects designed to ease overcrowding. The state
would pay only partial aid for other items, such as cafeterias and
media rooms, under the Assembly version.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to go by the court order. I don't know how we can get
around it,'' Sen. William Gormley, R-Atlantic, the bill sponsor,
told reporters after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Collins' position that the court did not order full funding
could only lead to more legal delays, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there would be action taken quickly and we'd be back
in court,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Collins has sought a judicial clarification to determine whether
the court in fact ordered full funding for the poor schools.
</P>
<P>
   Another growing concern about the bill is its ballooning
pricetag.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would provide about $6 billion in aid to the
special needs districts and $5.6 billion to the hundreds of others
not covered by the court order. Interest payments would bring the
final cost to about $15 billion over the 30-year repayment
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate version provides a minimum of 40 percent construction
funding for all school districts, in some cases retroactively.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he supports the minumum funding levels, but
believes the state also should set a ceiling on the amount of aid a
district receives.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to be nervous voting on a bill, whatever the amount
is, without any indication from the commissioner of Education of
what his standards might be,'' the speaker said.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley and other Senate supporters defended the inclusion of
the money for the suburban districts.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's only appropriate that when we solve and address the court
case, that we address the needs of the rest of the schools in the
state,'' he said. ''We tried to strike an accord for fundamental
fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Martin, R-Morris, chairman of the Senate Education
Committee, reminded lawmakers that the state can still practice
fiscal prudence.
</P>
<P>
   ''If a school asks for fluff, like a swimming pool or something
else that isn't absolutely essential, the state has the obligation
to turn it down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other differences between the competing bills include:
</P>
<P>
   -- The Senate would have the state Economic Development Authority
oversee the building project, the largest in state history, but
allows some local districts leeway to manage their own affairs.
Collins wants another state agency, the state Building Authority,
to head the effort.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Senate bill also includes six unidentified community
development projects to be built in conjunction with school
improvements, to upgrade entire neighborhoods. The Assembly version
has no such provision.	   The Assembly Appropriations Committee is expected to
take up the
lower house's version of the school construction bill on June 1,
with a full Assembly vote tentatively set for June 5.
</P>
<P>
   That gives the Legislature about two weeks to work out any
unresolved issues between the two bills, before the court's spring
deadline looms.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Full text of bills available at the Office of
Legislative Services Web site located at
http://www.njleg.state.nj.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
