<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Speaker retaliates against supporters of coup attempt  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- State Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver
retaliated Thursday against supporters of an ongoing attempted coup
by former Majority Leader Michael Bragman, and picked up the
backing of one of the chamber's most powerful members in the
battle.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman, the leader of the Assembly majority's more conservative
upstate wing, called the retaliatory moves by his fellow Democrat
''intolerable'' and boasted of enough support among Democratic
colleagues to send Silver packing.
</P>
<P>
   Silver spokeswoman Patricia Lynch said her boss was solidly in
control.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, supporters of the Manhattan Democrat were working
the telephones furiously behind the scenes on Thursday in an
attempt to turn back the Bragman challenge.
</P>
<P>
   That effort appeared to pay off, at least to some extent, when
Assemblyman Roberto Ramirez, the Democratic cdhairman of the Bronx,
announced Thursday night that he was backing Silver.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am absolutely, unequivocally, 100 percent behind Speaker
Sheldon Silver,'' Ramirez said, adding that the 10-member Bronx
Democratic delegation to the Assembly appeared to be in agreement
with him.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman went public with his coup attempt on Wednesday, saying
he planned to formally make his move Monday when the Assembly
reconvenes. Silver immediately stripped Bragman of the majority
leader's title and its $34,500-a-year, extra pay stipend and
temporarily closed the majority leader's state Capitol office.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman continued to work Thursday out of the majority leader's
office in the nearby Legislative Office Building.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Silver stripped two veteran members of the Assembly
of their committee chairmanships for supporting Bragman. Lynch did
not rule out further retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   In losing their chairmanships, Martin Luster of Ithaca and
Ronald Tocci of Westchester County also lost the $12,500 stipends
that go with the posts. New York's state legislators receive base
salaries of $79,500, but most also receive the extra stipends for
committee or party leadership posts. Assembly committee chairmen
serve at the pleasure of the speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Luster, elected to the Assembly in 1988, has been chairman of
the Assembly's Real Property Taxation Committee while Tocci,
elected to the chamber in 1984, has been head of the Veterans'
Affairs Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said it was an attempt to intimidate Assembly members
that would backfire and bring him even more support.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the kind of action that has prompted me doing what I
have done,'' he said, adding that it was a sign Silver was
''absolutely panic-stricken.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The members are very unhappy. They don't participate. They're
not part of the process. They are treated with disrespect,''
Bragman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sitting here this morning with 50 rock-solid (Democratic)
votes,'' he added. That would give the majority leader the
advantage within the 98-member Democratic majority in the
150-member house that will decide on Bragman's challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said he was considering making the names of his 50
colleagues public, but was hesitating because of possible further
retaliation by Silver.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're so treacherous in their actions here. They're so
heavy-handed that I am reluctant to put out the list,'' the
Syracuse-area Democrat said in an interview with The Associated
Press.
</P>
<P>
   In a later statement, Bragman said Silver's style has been
''secretive and aloof'' and that during the current leadership
battle ''he has surrounded himself with paid lobbyists and other
non-legislators who are seeking to influence members on how to vote
on this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Bragman's statement came out as several powerful New York labor
union leaders, including state AFL-CIO President Denis Hughes,
issued their own statement saying ''a divisive battle for the
speakership at this time is counterproductive.'' The statement did
not specifically endorse Silver.
</P>
<P>
   But just minutes later, a revised statement was issued by the
same labor leaders in which the claim that a leadership battle
would be counterproductive was removed. A spokesman for Hughes said
the first statement had been issued in error. The second statement
took no position on the wisdom of having a leadership fight.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman indicated he was being supported in his effort by state
Comptroller H. Carl McCall.
</P>
<P>
   ''As far as I am concerned, Carl and I are partners,'' Bragman
said.
</P>
<P>
   McCall said he was not helping either Silver or Bragman and that
when Assembly members called asking for advice, ''I'm telling them
that they've got to make a decision about what they want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Gov. George Pataki offered a similarly neutral stance
when current state Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno moved
successfully to oust Ralph Marino as the GOP leader of the Senate
over the Thanksgiving Day weekend in 1994. At the time, the Pataki
statement was viewed by many Republicans as the go-ahead for GOP
senators to join the revolt against Marino.
</P>
<P>
   McCall said the current situation was different. ''I'm not the
governor. I don't have that kind of influence ... I'm not involved.
It doesn't help me to be involved.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall, who is preparing for a run for governor in 2002, is the
only black ever elected to statewide office in New York and has
great sway with the Assembly's black lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the battle between Silver and Bragman stems at least in
part from the former majority leader's backing of McCall's
gubernatorial effort over federal Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo's
possible run for the job his father, Mario Cuomo, lost to Pataki in
1994. Silver has been widely seen as a Cuomo supporter.
</P>
<P>
   There was speculation Thursday that should it be evident by
Monday that Silver doesn't have the votes to remain as speaker,
some other Assembly Democrat from New York City may step forward to
challenge Bragman for the top job.
</P>
<P>
   There hasn't been a Democratic speaker of the Assembly from
outside New York City in more than 80 years. Should Bragman get the
job it would mean the city wouldn't have one of its own in the room
when Pataki, Bruno and the Assembly speaker negotiate budget deals
and other major issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
