<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Eyes Bigger Sierra Leone Force  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United Nations is preparing to
recommend a significant increase in the size of its Sierra Leone
peacekeeping force in hopes of propping up the West African
nation's peace process, diplomats and U.N. officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The officials, who spoke in New York and Freetown on condition
they not be identified, said Secretary-General Kofi Annan would
suggest the force be to as many as 16,500 in a report to be issued
later this week or next.
</P>
<P>
   The force, currently authorized at 11,100 troops, is already the
largest U.N. peacekeeping mission currently deployed.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council had been expected Thursday to approve a
stopgap British-sponsored resolution raising that limit to 13,000
in order to accommodate Indian, Jordanian and Bangladeshi troops
that have already been promised but haven't yet arrived.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States said it needed another day to consult
Congress for approval of the increase.
</P>
<P>
   In the next week or so, the council could take up Annan's new
recommendation for additional troops.
</P>
<P>
   West African countries, which supplied forces that kept the
peace in Sierra Leone before the U.N. presence, have already agreed
to send at least 3,000 additional reinforcements, said Elian Diop,
a spokeswoman for the West African political and economic
community, ECOWAS.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Russian President Vladimir Putin on Thursday urged
that Russian peacekeepers and helicopters be sent to the country.
Russia's Defense Ministry has prepared a contingent of four
helicopters and about 110 servicemen.
</P>
<P>
   The moves came despite widespread uncertainty about how the
peace agreement signed last July in Lome, Togo could be saved after
rebels took up arms against the government and United Nations
peacekeepers in the past few weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
