<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thursday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
World Focuses on Edmonton Researchers Diabetes Treatment
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- Diabetics worldwide clogged the phone
lines at a small medical foundation in an Edmonton industrial park
Thursday after it became the focus of a major breakthrough in
treating the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have got a lot of very, very emotional diabetics calling us
wanting to get in on the clinical trials,'' said Joanne Langer,
executive director of the Alberta Foundation for Diabetic Research.
</P>
<P>
   The group called a hasty news conference Thursday to discuss the
findings by a team of Alberta researchers it funded.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation also emphasized the importance of organ donations
after the potentially life-saving technique was described at a
medical conference in Chicago on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Phone calls from Israel, Germany, Australia and across the U.S.
and Canada were in response to news that a research team at the
University of Alberta in Edmonton has come close to a cure for the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   The team is the first in the world to successfully transplant
insulin-producing cells from a donor pancreas into the livers of
eight patients with severe diabetes.
Observers: Gas Prices Likely To Stay High All Summer
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Prices at the gas pumps across Canada crept up
again this week leading to the Victoria Day long weekend, and
industry watchers say higher world oil prices could make fill-ups
more expensive all summer.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike earlier this spring, when soaring prices were deflated by
a decision from the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
to pump more oil, fast relief isn't expected during the busy
driving season.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're in the high-demand period now,'' says Michael Ervin,
president of Calgary-based petroleum marketing firm M.J. Ervin &AMP;
Associates.
</P>
<P>
   ''So that alone is going to have an upward pressure on gasoline
prices right through until Labour Day weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Ervin's weekly pump price survey shows the national average
price rose 2.1 cents in the last week to 72.2 cents a litter. The
largest increase was in Windsor, Ontario, with an 8.4-cent jump to
73.7 cents a litter
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hunt, national president of the Canadian Automobile
Association, doesn't think extra gas costs will deter many from
getting on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   Many consumers are fighting back, with boycotts of the oil
majors or Internet-related efforts to track and publicize the
cheapest gas prices.
Nova Scotia Said Short More Than 600 Nurses
</P>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia (AP) -- Two newly released studies indicate
Nova Scotia is in dire need of more than 600 additional nurses.
</P>
<P>
   ''The point is quickly approaching where public safety will be
at risk,'' concludes a report on the nursing crisis presented to
Health Minister Jamie Muir in January.
</P>
<P>
   The documents were obtained by The Canadian Press under the
provincial Freedom of Information Act.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, four nurses who spoke at a news conference organized
by the NDP on Thursday said the crisis has already arrived.
</P>
<P>
   But Nova Scotia's Tory government says more research is needed.
