<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defense Bill Ups Veterans' Benefits  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A major defense bill passed by the House on
Thursday improves health care and prescription drug access for
military retirees and opens up all military hospitals to
Medicare-eligible vets.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which authorizes nearly $310 billion in defense
programs, also includes a 3.7 percent military pay raise and
provides up to $500 a month in assistance for economically strapped
military personnel, including those who depend on food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed 353-63 and now goes to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Health care for the nation's military retirees has become a
prominent issue in Congress as the retiree population ages and base
closings deprive them of many of health facilities near their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill seeks to improve TRICARE, the HMO-like health
care plan for retirees and military dependents. It eliminates
inequities where family members stationed far from military
facilities pay more for health care than those living near a base,
covers travel expenses for visits to facilities more than 100 miles
from primary care services and reduces limits on catastrophic
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   It also makes available a mail-order prescription drug service
to all Medicare-eligible retirees with an $8 copayment and a 20
percent copayment at network retail pharmacies. Currently, military
retirees, who switch to Medicare at age 65, can still get
prescription drugs but half can't take advantage of the benefit
because they don't live near a military base.
</P>
<P>
   The House, by 406-10, approved an amendment offered by Rep. Gene
Taylor, D-Miss., that would make permanent and nationwide a 1997
demonstration project under which six military health facilities
were opened to those 65 and older.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor argued that retirees ''justifiably feel betrayed''
because the nation has not lived up to the promise of a lifetime of
free health care at military facilities. ''They don't need any more
demonstration promises, they don't need any more halfhearted
efforts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Buyer, R-Ind., argued that military hospitals don't
have the space or the training to treat a large population of
elderly veterans and that the demonstration project, meant to be
cost-neutral, has cost the Pentagon more than $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   By making what is called Medicare subvention permanent ''we're
taking a crippled program that has not been fixed and putting it on
the road to financial disaster,'' he said. His proposal to add
sites to the current demonstration program was defeated 323-95.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration said it wanted the demonstration
project extended one or two years, after which expansion or its
lifetime could be evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers approved by 218-201 an amendment offered by Rep. Ike
Skelton, D-Mo., to remove language in the bill at odds with an
agreement reached last January between President Clinton and the
governor of Puerto Rico on the future of Navy training on the
Puerto Rican island of Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, growing out of long-lasting protests against live
ordnance training on Vieques, permitted the Navy to resume training
with dummy bombs and promised a referendum on whether the Navy
should leave Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill, however, would have barred the secretary of the
Navy from transferring the eastern end of the island from Navy
jurisdiction and allowed $40 million in economic aid to the people
of Vieques only when live-fire training was resumed on the range.
The administration, in a statement, said that provision would
unilaterally alter the agreement and was ''unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which provides $4.5 billion more than the
president requested, also contains $2.2 billion for research and
development of a national missile defense system and $5.9 billion
for Energy Department environmental cleanup programs.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers approved, 415-8, an amendment that would reduce from
180 to 60 days the congressional review period for administrative
changes in rules on high speed computers. They also voted 264-153
to end funds for U.S. ground troops in Kosovo if the president by
next April 1 doesn't certify that European allies are paying their
fair share in the peacekeeping mission.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill number is H.R. 4205.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The Armed Services Committee:
http://www.house.gov/hasc
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
