<HEADLINE> Weather hits hard in Hudson Valley  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y.(AP) -- About 100 homes were damaged as severe
thunderstorms over the state tore through sections of Orange,
Dutchess and Ulster counties.
</P>
<P>
   The Orange County Emergency Management Office reported high
winds, nickel-sized hail, torrential rains and scores of trees and
power lines blocking primary and secondary roads.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately, we've been through this with Floyd and other
storms; so we'll be able to do get through this one too,'' the
office's Dominick Greene said.
</P>
<P>
   Fallen power lines trapped several people in a car in the town
of Hamptonburgh 25 miles southwest of Poughkeepsie. Workers with
the Central Hudson Gas and Electric Corp. joined local firefighters
in freeing the passengers. None were seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   The three utility companies serving the area -- Central Hudson,
Orange and Rockland, and New York State Gas and Electric -- were
still figuring how many customers lost power to the storm as of
8:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   State Police in Ulster County said a collapsed tree about five
miles south of the Kingston Interchange backed traffic about three
miles.
</P>
<P>
   According to Trooper James Fulmer of the state police in
Poughkeepsie, detachment members spotted a funnel-shaped cloud.
National Weather Service meteorologists planned to survey the
damaged areas Friday to investigate the report.
</P>
<P>
   The same east-blowing storm ripped through most of the state.
</P>
<P>
   In Broome, Tioga and Chenango counties, several homes were
damaged by falling trees and blowing debris. NYSEG reported more
than 15,000 customers without power in the three-county area, with
many customers likely to be without power until Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Rush-hour traffic was slowed in Binghamton and surrounding
communities as streets were flooded and traffic signals stopped
operating.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said a house in Harpursville in northern Broome
county was damaged in a fire that may have been started by sparks
from downed electric lines.
</P>
</TEXT>
