<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Infamous Little Italy Eatery Reopens  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY McSHANE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Don't bother looking for bullet holes.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Umbertos Clam House -- the venerable Little Italy
institution where mobster ''Crazy Joey'' Gallo ate a lead dessert
after a last supper of scungilli -- hosted a grand reopening
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But no, this is not your godfather's restaurant. This Umbertos
is actually a new restaurant found two blocks from the original on
Mulberry Street. The lone constant is its owner, Bobby Ianniello,
who ran the old space between 1972-96.
</P>
<P>
   Ianniello, the brother of well-known Genovese family capo
Matthew ''Matty the Horse'' Ianniello, dismissed talk of the
restaurant's most infamous moment.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's 30 years ago,'' he said shortly before a party to
christen the new place. ''Joey Gallo -- kids today don't know his
name. That's not why people come here.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallo, a member of the Colombo crime family, became a celebrity
hoodlum of sorts in the early '70s -- surfacing at Broadway openings
and in gossip columns. His style and mouth often irritated his
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   One of those competitors helped Gallo turn Umbertos into an
indelible part of New York mob lore.
</P>
<P>
   In the early morning hours of April 7, 1972, Gallo arrived there
after a long night celebrating his 43rd birthday. Earlier, he
partied at the Copacabana with actor Jerry Orbach -- now a
television cop on ''Law &AMP; Order.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallo, accompanied by his bodyguard and a small entourage,
stopped in around 5 a.m. for a late-night snack.
</P>
<P>
   In a mistake he would never repeat, Gallo sat with his back to
the front door of the two-week-old restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   A hitman with a .38-caliber weapon entered. Bullets flew. Gallo,
mortally wounded, staggered to the street and died alongside his
parked Cadillac. No one was ever arrested for the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   After the hit, Matty Ianniello was reportedly cornered in
Umbertos kitchen by Gallo's bodyguard, ''Pete the Greek''
Diapioulas. When the bodyguard accused The Horse of setting Gallo
up, he quickly denied it.
</P>
<P>
   ''You think I'm crazy?'' Matty Ianniello asked. ''To let this
happen in this place?''
</P>
<P>
   The slaying immediately stamped Umbertos as a must-see for
tourists who scanned its woodwork and kitchen door for leftover
bullet holes. Its lure remained unabated, even when The Horse was
jailed in '86 for skimming its proceeds, or when a federal monitor
ran the place in the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   But the restaurant closed down in October 1996 after losing its
lease, Bobby Ianniello recounted. He opened a smaller restaurant
about a year later; the new space, with more than double the
seating of the old, officially opened this week.
</P>
<P>
   Why stay down on Mulberry Street?
</P>
<P>
   ''It's still the character of the neighborhood,'' Ianniello
replied. ''It's old New York. And the fact that it still attracts
many tourists -- Little Italy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-18-00 2136 </TRAILER>
