<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defender Da Guia Dies at 87  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Defender Domingos da Guia, whose
elegant style of play earned him the nickname the ''Divine
Master,'' died Thursday of complications following a stroke. He was
87.
</P>
<P>
   Da Guia starred in the 1930s and 1940s for the Brazilian club
soccer teams Bangu, Flamengo, Vasco da Gama and Corinthians,
winning Rio de Janeiro state championships in 1934, 1939, 1942 and
1943. He also won titles for Nacional of Uruguay in 1933 and for
Argentina's Boca Juniors in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   Da Guia, using technique rather than force, set the standard by
which all Brazilian defenders came to be judged. He started on the
Brazilian team that finished third at the 1938 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   His son, Ademir da Guia, inherited his father's style and also
became a star player. As a midfielder with Palmeiras, he won
national championships in 1972 and 1973 and played in the 1974
World Cup, where Brazil finished fourth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
