<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate closes loophole in nude bathing ban  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The state Senate on Thursday closed a
loophole in a law banning nude bathing that allowed swimmers to
sunbathe naked on federal land within the state.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, S-1225, clarifies current law to ensure that no one
can disrobe on government-owned land. It passed 36-0.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by Sen. James Cafiero, R-Cape May, the bill amends a
1999 law that said a town could forbid nudity only on ''state owned
lands within its borders.''
</P>
<P>
   After passage of that law, nude bathers found a loophole because
part of Higbee Beach in Lower Township is owned by the United
States, and not the state of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The revised measure would allow towns to prohibit nudity on all
land ''under the jurisdiction of the state,'' which includes both
the state and federally owned sections of the popular Cape May
County beach.
</P>
<P>
   The bill heads to the Assembly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
