<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vegetable stand, other businesses, teeter on edge of roadside precipice </HEADLINE>
Pursuing AP Photo
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, N.Y. (AP) -- A vegetable stand teetering for two days
on the brink of a steep roadside toppled Thursday in the aftermath
of a mudslide that dammed the creek below, threatening the city of
Albany's main water line.
</P>
<P>
   The California Produce Market had lost a good portion of the
land beneath it to a landslide Tuesday; officials said Thursday's
severe thunderstorms only hastened the inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Both a car wash and an instant oil change business were forced
to close indefinitely due to lost ground.
</P>
<P>
   ''It looks like we're going to be shut down for a while,'' said
Tom Hoffman of Hoffman's car wash.
</P>
<P>
   Bethlehem police and Albany Mayor Jerry Jennings were among many
officials staked out at a command post along the well-traveled
Delaware Avenue linking downtown Albany with one of the city's more
affluent suburban areas. Huge chunks of the avenue had already
fallen away and the road was closed indefinitely. Officials were
contemplating evacuation of nearby homes.
</P>
<P>
   Town of Bethlehem Supervisor Sheila Fuller declared a local
state of emergency.
</P>
<P>
   The landslide late Tuesday displaced about 400 linear feet of
earth, trees, and shrubs, which slid into the Normans Kill below,
creating a wall of dirt and vegetation that blocked off the creek.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was like a blanket of earth just slid down the hill,'' said
John Keller of William J. Keller &AMP; Sons Construction Co., the
city's emergency contractor.
</P>
<P>
   City Water Commissioner Robert Cross worried that the Normans
Kill would cut a new channel underneath the main, forcing it above
ground or bursting it. Keller &AMP; Sons worked through the night to
cut through between 2,000 and 3,000 of yards of earth and form a
new path for the creek.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the produce stand, the crumbling ground
threatened a commercial car wash and an instant oil change
business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
