<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Florio, Corzine face final debate in Democratic primary for Senate  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDISON, N.J. (AP) -- In the last scheduled face-to-face meeting
before the Democratic primary election for U.S. Senate, former Gov.
Jim Florio found himself defending his credibility against the
attacks of his opponent, Jon Corzine.
</P>
<P>
   While Florio had been aiming in four debates over the past week
to throw his less experienced opponent off balance or to goad him
into a mistake, Thursday's debate, broadcast live from the studios
of the News 12 New Jersey cable television station, had Florio
trying to recover from a mistake of his own.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Jewish News weekly newspaper this week released a
tape recording in which Florio explicitly supported the idea of
investing Social Security funds in the stock market. He made the
remark at a forum in May 1999 before Corzine was in the race, and
his campaign now says he misspoke at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Corzine entered the race and proposed investment of
Social Security funds, Florio has centered caustic attacks against
Corzine on the issue, doing it again Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''The transcript that came out clearly indicates I misspoke. I
did not think it was a good idea in the past. I do not think it is
a good idea now,'' Florio said. ''Volatility is not compatible with
security.''
</P>
<P>
   But the controversy over the tape gave Corzine fuel for
counterattacking, something at which he has become more adept as
the week of debates has unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine said the disclosure of the remarks destroyed Florio's
credibility. ''Today we have learned that for an entire year, he
has been misleading the voters about his position on Social
Security.''
</P>
<P>
   The format of the debate prevented the candidates from attacking
one another as much as in previous debates, but they managed to get
a few shots in.
</P>
<P>
   ''For my opponent, the truth sometimes is a political
inconvenience,'' Corzine said. ''He says he has experience money
can't buy. The truth is he has given us an experience we would
rather forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio continued to try to depict Corzine, a former executive at
the Goldman Sachs investment firm, as untrustworthy because his
work at the firm conflicts with the promises he is making now
regarding, for instance, gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ''While I was taking on the gun lobby, Jon was financing the gun
industry,'' Florio said. ''This whole thing comes down to if you
send one of us to Washington, who is going to go down there to
represent Wall Street, and who is going to go down there to
represent Main Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine replied, ''I have a very, very strong position with
regard to guns, and there is nothing in the history of Goldman
Sachs that is going to limit my feeling on that.''
</P>
<P>
   The sequence of four Democratic debates began one week ago at
New Jersey Network studios, the state's public television station.
The candidates also debated Monday morning at a New York City radio
station and Tuesday night before an audience of 500 in Livingston.
</P>
<P>
   Florio has criticized Corzine for refusing to attend a debate
with the League of Women Voters to be taped next Friday and aired
on ABC-TV network affiliates in New York and Philadelphia. It would
have been the only one to be shown on network television, where
Corzine has been spending millions of dollars a week in a blitz of
TV commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine defended his decision not to debate on network
television.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just think the debate about the debates is not focused on
prescription drug benefits and the kinds of things people want to
hear candidates talk about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Florio said, ''If you are going to spend $2 million a week on
television beating me up, come and have the guts to discuss whether
he supports property tax relief or not.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I have for a year been trying to get Jon to engage in a
debate. We have (had) four in the last couple of days, but this is
not mass audience. The people of this state are going to be called
upon to vote for someone they know absolutely nothing about,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Munich of WPVI-TV said air time has been reserved and they
would be able to schedule the debate until the last minute next
Thursday if Corzine were to change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   The election will be held June 6.
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.news12.com/newjersey/nj.html
</P>
<P>
   http://www.votecorzine.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.florionj.com
</P>
</TEXT>
