<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weather hits hard in Hudson Valley, Southern Tier, funnel clouds reported </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y.(AP) -- About 100 homes were damaged as severe
thunderstorms plowing through the state hit especially hard in the
Hudson Valley.
</P>
<P>
   National Weather Service meteorologists said they planned to do
on-site investigations following several reports of funnel clouds
touching down in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Orange, Dutchess and Ulster counties, the storm's
powerful winds blew off roofs and left streets carpeted with leaves
and broken branches. Pounding rain and pelting hail tore of
rooftops and punched out lights for thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Hail the size of marbles bombarded Sullivan County, and
three-quarter-inch hail was reported in surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>
   In Orange and Sullivan counties, some 15,000 Orange and Rockland
Utilities customers lost power, said spokesman Jim Lois. As of 9
p.m., 13,000 O&AMP;R customers were still in the dark. Some 52,000
customers of Central Hudson Gas &AMP; Electric's 8-county area were
without power, with company officials saying some of them could be
in the dark until Saturday. Widespread power outages were also
reported in the Albany-Schenectady-Troy area as well as Columbia
County to the south. Outage estimates for New York State Electric
and Gas customers were not immediately available Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The power outage forced Ulster County Community College to
postpone its graduation.
</P>
<P>
   On Route 211 in the Ulster County town of Wallkill, roofers Gary
Curtis and Barry Johnson say they saw funnel clouds touch down,
blowing the roof off a German deli.
</P>
<P>
   ''We saw the roof fly off and figured we better pull in to see
if we could help,'' Curtis told the Middletown Times Herald-Record.
Rain was pouring through the roof at the Home Depot where the duo
went to buy a tarp.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was raining inside as hard as it was outside,'' Curtis
said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the state police in Poughkeepsie say they too spotted
a funnel-shaped cloud.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency workers closed much of Route 211 as bits of shredded
roof material littered the roadway.
</P>
<P>
   Fallen power lines trapped several people in a car in the town
of Hamptonburgh 25 miles southwest of Poughkeepsie. Workers with
the Central Hudson Gas and Electric Corp. joined local firefighters
in freeing the passengers. None were seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   State Police in Ulster County said a collapsed tree about five
miles south of the Kingston Interchange backed traffic about three
miles.
</P>
<P>
   The same east-blowing caused damage across the state.
</P>
<P>
   In Broome, Tioga and Chenango counties, several homes were
damaged by falling trees and blowing debris. NYSEG reported more
than 15,000 customers without power in the three-county area, with
many customers likely to be without power until Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Rush-hour traffic was slowed in Binghamton and surrounding
communities as streets were flooded and traffic signals stopped
operating.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said a house in Harpursville in northern Broome
county was damaged in a fire that may have been started by sparks
from downed electric lines.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service issued overnight flood watches for
the western Southern Tier, including Allegany, Cattaraugus, and
Chautauqua counties. Meteorologists said a low pressure system over
northern Indiana was expected to bring batch of rain and
thunderstorms across lower Michigan and western Lake Erie and
across the Southern Tier after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the state, Friday's forecast called for brisk
winds, cool weather, and possible showers.
</P>
<P>
   In Montgomery County west of Schenectady, a barn was reported
missing.
</P>
<P>
   ''It blew away,'' said Dispatcher Adam Schwabrow of the
Montgomery County Sheriff's Department.
</P>
<P>
   The barn was found after the storm subsided, several hundred
feet away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
